(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[116],{YFeS:function(e){e.exports=[{id:1,type:"  vsphere_license",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"license_key",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The license key to add.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"labels",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A map of key/value pairs to be attached as labels (tags) to the license key.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/license.html",docType:""},{id:2,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the cluster.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe datacenter to create the cluster in. Forces a new resource if changed.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The relative path to a folder to put this cluster in.\nThis is a path relative to the datacenter you are deploying the cluster to.\nExample: for the <code>dc1</code> datacenter, and a provided <code>folder</code> of <code>foo/bar</code>,\nTerraform will place a cluster named <code>terraform-compute-cluster-test</code> in a\nhost folder located at <code>/dc1/host/foo/bar</code>, with the final inventory path\nbeing <code>/dc1/host/foo/bar/terraform-datastore-cluster-test</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support requires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A map of custom attribute ids to attribute\nvalue strings to set for the datastore cluster. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values\nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"host-management-options",description:'<h3 id="host-management-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#host-management-options" name="host-management-options">\xbb</a>\n  Host management options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings control cluster membership or tune how hosts are managed\nwithin the cluster itself by Terraform.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"host_system_ids",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object IDs</a> of\nthe hosts to put in the cluster.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_cluster_exit_timeout",description:"The timeout for each host maintenance mode\noperation when removing hosts from a cluster. The value is specified in\nseconds. Default: <code>3600</code> (1 hour).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"force_evacuate_on_destroy",description:'When destroying the resource, setting this to\n<code>true</code> will auto-remove any hosts that are currently a member of the cluster,\nas if they were removed by taking their entry out of <code>host_system_ids</code> (see\n<a href="#how-terraform-removes-hosts-from-clusters">below</a>). This is an advanced\noption and should only be used for testing. Default: <code>false</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Do not set <code>force_evacuate_on_destroy</code> in production operation as\nthere are many pitfalls to its use when working with complex cluster\nconfigurations. Depending on the virtual machines currently on the cluster, and\nyour DRS and HA settings, the full host evacuation may fail. Instead,\nincrementally remove hosts from your configuration by adjusting the contents of\nthe <code>host_system_ids</code> attribute.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"how-terraform-removes-hosts-from-clusters",description:'<h4 id="how-terraform-removes-hosts-from-clusters">\n<a class="anchor" href="#how-terraform-removes-hosts-from-clusters" name="how-terraform-removes-hosts-from-clusters">\xbb</a>\n  How Terraform removes hosts from clusters\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>One can remove hosts from clusters by adjusting the\n<a href="#host_system_ids"><code>host_system_ids</code></a> configuration setting and removing the\nhosts in question. Hosts are removed sequentially, by placing them in\nmaintenance mode, <em>moving them</em> to the root host folder in vSphere inventory,\nand then taking the host out of maintenance mode. This process, if successful,\npreserves the host in vSphere inventory as a standalone host.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<p>Note that whether or not this operation succeeds as intended depends on your\nDRS and high availability settings. To ensure as much as possible that this\noperation will succeed, ensure that no HA configuration depends on the host\n<em>before</em> applying the host removal operation, as host membership operations are\nprocessed before configuration is applied. If there are VMs on the host, set\nyour <a href="#drs_automation_level"><code>drs_automation_level</code></a> to <code>fullyAutomated</code> to\nensure that DRS can correctly evacuate the host before removal.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Note that all virtual machines are migrated as part of the maintenance mode\noperation, including ones that are powered off or suspended. Ensure there is\nenough capacity on your remaining hosts to accommodate the extra load.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"drs-automation-options",description:'<h3 id="drs-automation-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#drs-automation-options" name="drs-automation-options">\xbb</a>\n  DRS automation options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control the settings for DRS on the cluster.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"drs_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable DRS for this cluster. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_automation_level",description:" <strong>(Optional)</strong> The default automation level for all\nvirtual machines in this cluster. Can be one of <code>manual</code>,\n<code>partiallyAutomated</code>, or <code>fullyAutomated</code>. Default: <code>manual</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_migration_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A value between <code>1</code> and <code>5</code> indicating\nthe threshold of imbalance tolerated between hosts. A lower setting will\ntolerate more imbalance while a higher setting will tolerate less. Default:\n<code>3</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_enable_vm_overrides",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow individual DRS overrides to be\nset for virtual machines in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_enable_predictive_drs",description:'<li><p><a name="drs_enable_predictive_drs"></a><a href="#drs_enable_predictive_drs"><code>drs_enable_predictive_drs</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When <code>true</code>, enables DRS to use data\nfrom <a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/vRealize-Operations-Manager/index.html">vRealize Operations Manager</a> to make proactive DRS\nrecommendations. <sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup></p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_advanced_options",description:'<li><p><a name="drs_advanced_options"></a><a href="#drs_advanced_options"><code>drs_advanced_options</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> A key/value map that specifies advanced\noptions for DRS and <a href="#dpm-options">DPM</a>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dpm-options",description:'<h4 id="dpm-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#dpm-options" name="dpm-options">\xbb</a>\n  DPM options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings control the <a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.resmgmt.doc/GUID-5E5E349A-4644-4C9C-B434-1C0243EBDC80.html#GUID-5E5E349A-4644-4C9C-B434-1C0243EBDC80">Distributed Power\nManagement</a> (DPM) settings for the cluster. DPM allows the\ncluster to manage host capacity on-demand depending on the needs of the\ncluster, powering on hosts when capacity is needed, and placing hosts in\nstandby when there is excess capacity in the cluster.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"dpm_enabled",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable DPM support for DRS in this cluster.\nRequires <a href="#drs_enabled"><code>drs_enabled</code></a> to be <code>true</code> in order to be effective.\nDefault: <code>false</code>. \n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dpm_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The automation level for host power\noperations in this cluster. Can be one of <code>manual</code> or <code>automated</code>. Default:\n<code>manual</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dpm_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A value between <code>1</code> and <code>5</code> indicating the\nthreshold of load within the cluster that influences host power operations.\nThis affects both power on and power off operations",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vsphere-ha-options",description:'<h3 id="vsphere-ha-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vsphere-ha-options" name="vsphere-ha-options">\xbb</a>\n  vSphere HA Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings control the <a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.avail.doc/GUID-5432CA24-14F1-44E3-87FB-61D937831CF6.html">vSphere HA</a>\nsettings for the cluster.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> vSphere HA has a number of requirements that should be met to\nensure that any configured settings work correctly. For a full list, see the\n<a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.avail.doc/GUID-BA85FEC4-A37C-45BA-938D-37B309010D93.html">vSphere HA Checklist</a>.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"ha_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable vSphere HA for this cluster. Default:\n<code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_host_monitoring",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Global setting that controls whether\nvSphere HA remediates virtual machines on host failure. Can be one of <code>enabled</code>\nor <code>disabled</code>. Default: <code>enabled</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_restart_priority",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The default restart priority\nfor affected virtual machines when vSphere detects a host failure. Can be one\nof <code>lowest</code>, <code>low</code>, <code>medium</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>highest</code>. Default: <code>medium</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_dependency_restart_condition",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The condition used to\ndetermine whether or not virtual machines in a certain restart priority class\nare online, allowing HA to move on to restarting virtual machines on the next\npriority. Can be one of <code>none</code>, <code>poweredOn</code>, <code>guestHbStatusGreen</code>, or\n<code>appHbStatusGreen</code>. The default is <code>none</code>, which means that a virtual machine\nis considered ready immediately after a host is found to start it on.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_restart_additional_delay",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Additional delay in seconds\nafter ready condition is met. A VM is considered ready at this point.\nDefault: <code>0</code> (no delay). <sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_restart_timeout",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum time, in seconds,\nthat vSphere HA will wait for virtual machines in one priority to be ready\nbefore proceeding with the next priority. Default: <code>600</code> (10 minutes).\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_host_isolation_response",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The action to take on virtual\nmachines when a host has detected that it has been isolated from the rest of\nthe cluster. Can be one of <code>none</code>, <code>powerOff</code>, or <code>shutdown</code>. Default:\n<code>none</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_advanced_options",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A key/value map that specifies advanced\noptions for vSphere HA.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings",description:'<h4 id="ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings" name="ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings">\xbb</a>\n  HA Virtual Machine Component Protection settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings control Virtual Machine Component Protection (VMCP) in\nvSphere HA. VMCP gives vSphere HA the ability to monitor a host for datastore\naccessibility failures, and automate recovery for affected virtual machines.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">\n<p><strong>Note on terminology:</strong> In VMCP, Permanent Device Loss (PDL), or a failure\nwhere access to a specific disk device is not recoverable, is differentiated\nfrom an All Paths Down (APD) failure, which is used to denote a transient\nfailure where disk device access may eventually return. Take note of this when\ntuning these options.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"ha_vm_component_protection",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls vSphere VM component\nprotection for virtual machines in this cluster. Can be one of <code>enabled</code> or\n<code>disabled</code>. Default: <code>enabled</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_pdl_response",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take on\nvirtual machines when the cluster has detected a permanent device loss to a\nrelevant datastore. Can be one of <code>disabled</code>, <code>warning</code>, or\n<code>restartAggressive</code>. Default: <code>disabled</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_response",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take on\nvirtual machines when the cluster has detected loss to all paths to a\nrelevant datastore. Can be one of <code>disabled</code>, <code>warning</code>,\n<code>restartConservative</code>, or <code>restartAggressive</code>.  Default: <code>disabled</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_recovery_action",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take\non virtual machines if an APD status on an affected datastore clears in the\nmiddle of an APD event. Can be one of <code>none</code> or <code>reset</code>. Default: <code>none</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_response_delay",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the delay in minutes\nto wait after an APD timeout event to execute the response action defined in\n<a href="#ha_datastore_apd_response"><code>ha_datastore_apd_response</code></a>. Default: <code>3</code>\nminutes. <sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings",description:'<h4 id="ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings" name="ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings">\xbb</a>\n  HA virtual machine and application monitoring settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings illustrate the options that can be set to work with\nvirtual machine and application monitoring on vSphere HA.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_vm_monitoring",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of virtual machine monitoring to use\nwhen HA is enabled in the cluster. Can be one of <code>vmMonitoringDisabled</code>,\n<code>vmMonitoringOnly</code>, or <code>vmAndAppMonitoring</code>. Default: <code>vmMonitoringDisabled</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_failure_interval",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If a heartbeat from a virtual machine\nis not received within this configured interval, the virtual machine is\nmarked as failed. The value is in seconds. Default: <code>30</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_minimum_uptime",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The time, in seconds, that HA waits after\npowering on a virtual machine before monitoring for heartbeats. Default:\n<code>120</code> (2 minutes).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_maximum_resets",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum number of resets that HA will\nperform to a virtual machine when responding to a failure event. Default: <code>3</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_maximum_failure_window",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The length of the reset window in\nwhich <a href="#ha_vm_maximum_resets"><code>ha_vm_maximum_resets</code></a> can operate. When this\nwindow expires, no more resets are attempted regardless of the setting\nconfigured in <code>ha_vm_maximum_resets</code>. <code>-1</code> means no window, meaning an\nunlimited reset time is allotted. The value is specified in seconds. Default:\n<code>-1</code> (no window).\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vsphere-ha-admission-control-settings",description:'<h4 id="vsphere-ha-admission-control-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vsphere-ha-admission-control-settings" name="vsphere-ha-admission-control-settings">\xbb</a>\n  vSphere HA Admission Control settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings control vSphere HA Admission Control, which controls\nwhether or not specific VM operations are permitted in the cluster in order to\nprotect the reliability of the cluster. Based on the constraints defined in\nthese settings, operations such as power on or migration operations may be\nblocked to ensure that enough capacity remains to react to host failures.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"admission-control-modes",description:'<h4 id="admission-control-modes">\n<a class="anchor" href="#admission-control-modes" name="admission-control-modes">\xbb</a>\n  Admission control modes\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The <a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a> parameter\ncontrols the specific mode that Admission Control uses. What settings are\navailable depends on the admission control mode:</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_policy",description:'<li><strong>Cluster resource percentage</strong>: This is the default admission control mode,\nand allows you to specify a percentage of the cluster\'s CPU and memory\nresources to reserve as spare capacity, or have these settings automatically\ndetermined by failure tolerance levels. To use, set\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a> to\n<code>resourcePercentage</code>.\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_policy",description:'<li><strong>Slot Policy (powered-on VMs)</strong>: This allows the definition of a virtual\nmachine "slot", which is a set amount of CPU and memory resources that should\nrepresent the size of an average virtual machine in the cluster. To use, set\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a> to\n<code>slotPolicy</code>.\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_policy",description:'<li><strong>Dedicated failover hosts</strong>: This allows the reservation of dedicated\nfailover hosts. Admission Control will block access to these hosts for normal\noperation to ensure that they are available for failover events. In the event\nthat a dedicated host does not enough capacity, hosts that are not part of\nthe dedicated pool will still be used for overflow if possible. To use, set\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a> to\n<code>failoverHosts</code>.\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<p>It is also possible to disable Admission Control by setting\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a> to <code>disabled</code>,\nhowever this is not recommended as it can lead to issues with cluster capacity,\nand instability with vSphere HA.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_policy",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of admission control\npolicy to use with vSphere HA. Can be one of <code>resourcePercentage</code>,\n<code>slotPolicy</code>, <code>failoverHosts</code>, or <code>disabled</code>. Default: <code>resourcePercentage</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"common-admission-control-settings",description:'<h4 id="common-admission-control-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#common-admission-control-settings" name="common-admission-control-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Common Admission Control settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings are available for all Admission Control modes, but will\ninfer different meanings in each mode.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_host_failure_tolerance",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum number\nof failed hosts that admission control tolerates when making decisions on\nwhether to permit virtual machine operations. The maximum is one less than\nthe number of hosts in the cluster. Default: <code>1</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_performance_tolerance",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The percentage of\nresource reduction that a cluster of virtual machines can tolerate in case of\na failover. A value of 0 produces warnings only, whereas a value of 100\ndisables the setting. Default: <code>100</code> (disabled).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"admission-control-settings-for-resource-percentage-mode",description:'<h4 id="admission-control-settings-for-resource-percentage-mode">\n<a class="anchor" href="#admission-control-settings-for-resource-percentage-mode" name="admission-control-settings-for-resource-percentage-mode">\xbb</a>\n  Admission Control settings for resource percentage mode\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings control specific settings for Admission Control when\n<code>resourcePercentage</code> is selected in\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_resource_percentage_auto_compute",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong>\nAutomatically determine available resource percentages by subtracting the\naverage number of host resources represented by the\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_host_failure_tolerance"><code>ha_admission_control_host_failure_tolerance</code></a>\nsetting from the total amount of resources in the cluster. Disable to supply\nuser-defined values. Default: <code>true</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_resource_percentage_cpu",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the\nuser-defined percentage of CPU resources in the cluster to reserve for\nfailover. Default: <code>100</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_resource_percentage_memory",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the\nuser-defined percentage of memory resources in the cluster to reserve for\nfailover. Default: <code>100</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"admission-control-settings-for-slot-policy-mode",description:'<h4 id="admission-control-settings-for-slot-policy-mode">\n<a class="anchor" href="#admission-control-settings-for-slot-policy-mode" name="admission-control-settings-for-slot-policy-mode">\xbb</a>\n  Admission Control settings for slot policy mode\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings control specific settings for Admission Control when\n<code>slotPolicy</code> is selected in\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_slot_policy_use_explicit_size",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls\nwhether or not you wish to supply explicit values to CPU and memory slot\nsizes. The default is <code>false</code>, which tells vSphere to gather a automatic\naverage based on all powered-on virtual machines currently in the cluster.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_slot_policy_explicit_cpu",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the\nuser-defined CPU slot size, in MHz. Default: <code>32</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_admission_control_slot_policy_explicit_memory",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the\nuser-defined memory slot size, in MB. Default: <code>100</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"admission-control-settings-for-dedicated-failover-host-mode",description:'<h4 id="admission-control-settings-for-dedicated-failover-host-mode">\n<a class="anchor" href="#admission-control-settings-for-dedicated-failover-host-mode" name="admission-control-settings-for-dedicated-failover-host-mode">\xbb</a>\n  Admission Control settings for dedicated failover host mode\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings control specific settings for Admission Control when\n<code>failoverHosts</code> is selected in\n<a href="#ha_admission_control_policy"><code>ha_admission_control_policy</code></a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_admission_control_failover_host_system_ids",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Defines the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object IDs</a> of hosts to use as dedicated failover\nhosts. These hosts are kept as available as possible',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vsphere-ha-datastore-settings",description:'<h4 id="vsphere-ha-datastore-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vsphere-ha-datastore-settings" name="vsphere-ha-datastore-settings">\xbb</a>\n  vSphere HA datastore settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>vSphere HA uses datastore heartbeating to determine the health of a particular\nhost. Depending on how your datastores are configured, the settings below may\nneed to be altered to ensure that specific datastores are used over others.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<p>If you require a user-defined list of datastores, ensure you select either\n<code>userSelectedDs</code> (for user selected only) or <code>allFeasibleDsWithUserPreference</code>\n(for automatic selection with preferred overrides) for the\n<a href="#ha_heartbeat_datastore_policy"><code>ha_heartbeat_datastore_policy</code></a> setting.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_heartbeat_datastore_policy",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The selection policy for HA\nheartbeat datastores. Can be one of <code>allFeasibleDs</code>, <code>userSelectedDs</code>, or\n<code>allFeasibleDsWithUserPreference</code>. Default:\n<code>allFeasibleDsWithUserPreference</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_heartbeat_datastore_ids",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The list of managed object IDs for\npreferred datastores to use for HA heartbeating. This setting is only useful\nwhen <a href="#ha_heartbeat_datastore_policy"><code>ha_heartbeat_datastore_policy</code></a> is set\nto either <code>userSelectedDs</code> or <code>allFeasibleDsWithUserPreference</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"proactive-ha-settings",description:'<h4 id="proactive-ha-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#proactive-ha-settings" name="proactive-ha-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Proactive HA settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings pertain to <a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.avail.doc/GUID-3E3B18CC-8574-46FA-9170-CF549B8E55B8.html">Proactive HA</a>, an\nadvanced feature of vSphere HA that allows the cluster to get data from\nexternal providers and make decisions based on the data reported.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Working with Proactive HA is outside the scope of this document. For more\ndetails, see the referenced link in the above paragraph.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"proactive_ha_enabled",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enables Proactive HA. Default: <code>false</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"proactive_ha_automation_level",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines how the host\nquarantine, maintenance mode, or virtual machine migration recommendations\nmade by proactive HA are to be handled. Can be one of <code>Automated</code> or\n<code>Manual</code>. Default: <code>Manual</code>. <sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"proactive_ha_moderate_remediation",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The configured remediation\nfor moderately degraded hosts. Can be one of <code>MaintenanceMode</code> or\n<code>QuarantineMode</code>. Note that this cannot be set to <code>MaintenanceMode</code> when\n<a href="#proactive_ha_severe_remediation"><code>proactive_ha_severe_remediation</code></a> is set\nto <code>QuarantineMode</code>. Default: <code>QuarantineMode</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"proactive_ha_severe_remediation",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The configured remediation for\nseverely degraded hosts. Can be one of <code>MaintenanceMode</code> or <code>QuarantineMode</code>.\nNote that this cannot be set to <code>QuarantineMode</code> when\n<a href="#proactive_ha_moderate_remediation"><code>proactive_ha_moderate_remediation</code></a> is\nset to <code>MaintenanceMode</code>. Default: <code>QuarantineMode</code>.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"proactive_ha_provider_ids",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The list of IDs for health update\nproviders configured for this cluster.\n<sup><a href="#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html",docType:""},{id:3,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_host_group",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the host group. This must be unique in the\ncluster. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="host_system_ids"></a><a href="#host_system_ids"><code>host_system_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object IDs</a> of\nthe hosts to put in the cluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for cluster names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_group.html"><code>vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_group</code></a>\nresource. Make sure your names are unique across both resources.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_host_group.html",docType:""},{id:4,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_affinity_rule",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"name",description:'<li><p><a name="name"></a><a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the rule. This must be unique in the cluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_ids"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_ids"><code>virtual_machine_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUIDs of the virtual machines to run\non the same host together.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="enabled"></a><a href="#enabled"><code>enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable this rule in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mandatory",description:'<li><p><a name="mandatory"></a><a href="#mandatory"><code>mandatory</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this value is <code>true</code>, prevents any virtual\nmachine operations that may violate this rule. Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for rule names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with all rules in the cluster - consider\nthis when naming your rules.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_affinity_rule.html",docType:""},{id:5,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_anti_affinity_rule",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"name",description:'<li><p><a name="name"></a><a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the rule. This must be unique in the cluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_ids"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_ids"><code>virtual_machine_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUIDs of the virtual machines to run\non hosts different from each other.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="enabled"></a><a href="#enabled"><code>enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable this rule in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mandatory",description:'<li><p><a name="mandatory"></a><a href="#mandatory"><code>mandatory</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this value is <code>true</code>, prevents any virtual\nmachine operations that may violate this rule. Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for rule names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with all rules in the cluster - consider\nthis when naming your rules.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_anti_affinity_rule.html",docType:""},{id:6,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_dependency_rule",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"name",description:'<li><p><a name="name"></a><a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the rule. This must be unique in the\ncluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dependency_vm_group_name",description:'<li><p><a name="dependency_vm_group_name"></a><a href="#dependency_vm_group_name"><code>dependency_vm_group_name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the VM group that this\nrule depends on. The VMs defined in the group specified by\n<a href="#vm_group_name"><code>vm_group_name</code></a> will not be started until the VMs in this\ngroup are started.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vm_group_name",description:'<li><p><a name="vm_group_name"></a><a href="#vm_group_name"><code>vm_group_name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the VM group that is the subject of\nthis rule. The VMs defined in this group will not be started until the VMs in\nthe group specified by\n<a href="#dependency_vm_group_name"><code>dependency_vm_group_name</code></a> are started.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="enabled"></a><a href="#enabled"><code>enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable this rule in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mandatory",description:'<li><p><a name="mandatory"></a><a href="#mandatory"><code>mandatory</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this value is <code>true</code>, prevents any virtual\nmachine operations that may violate this rule. Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for rule names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with all rules in the cluster - consider\nthis when naming your rules.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_dependency_rule.html",docType:""},{id:7,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_group",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the VM group. This must be unique in the\ncluster. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_ids"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_ids"><code>virtual_machine_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUIDs of the virtual machines in this\ngroup.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for cluster names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_host_group.html"><code>vsphere_compute_cluster_host_group</code></a>\nresource. Make sure your names are unique across both resources.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_group.html",docType:""},{id:8,type:"  vsphere_compute_cluster_vm_host_rule",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the group in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"name",description:'<li><p><a name="name"></a><a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the rule. This must be unique in the\ncluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vm_group_name",description:'<li><p><a name="vm_group_name"></a><a href="#vm_group_name"><code>vm_group_name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the virtual machine group to use\nwith this rule.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"affinity_host_group_name",description:'<li><p><a name="affinity_host_group_name"></a><a href="#affinity_host_group_name"><code>affinity_host_group_name</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this field is used, the virtual\nmachines defined in <a href="#vm_group_name"><code>vm_group_name</code></a> will be run on the\nhosts defined in this host group.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"anti_affinity_host_group_name",description:'<li><p><a name="anti_affinity_host_group_name"></a><a href="#anti_affinity_host_group_name"><code>anti_affinity_host_group_name</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this field is used, the\nvirtual machines defined in <a href="#vm_group_name"><code>vm_group_name</code></a> will <em>not</em> be\nrun on the hosts defined in this host group.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="enabled"></a><a href="#enabled"><code>enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable this rule in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mandatory",description:'<li><p><a name="mandatory"></a><a href="#mandatory"><code>mandatory</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> When this value is <code>true</code>, prevents any virtual\nmachine operations that may violate this rule. Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> One of <a href="#affinity_host_group_name"><code>affinity_host_group_name</code></a> or\n<a href="#anti_affinity_host_group_name"><code>anti_affinity_host_group_name</code></a> must be\ndefined, but not both.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The namespace for rule names on this resource (defined by the\n<a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> argument) is shared with all rules in the cluster - consider\nthis when naming your rules.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster_vm_host_rule.html",docType:""},{id:9,type:"  vsphere_drs_vm_override",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the override in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_id",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_id"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_id"><code>virtual_machine_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUID of the virtual machine to create\nthe override for.  Forces a new resource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="drs_enabled"></a><a href="#drs_enabled"><code>drs_enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default DRS setting for this virtual\nmachine. Can be either <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>. Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"drs_automation_level",description:'<li><p><a name="drs_automation_level"></a><a href="#drs_automation_level"><code>drs_automation_level</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the automation level for this virtual\nmachine in the cluster. Can be one of <code>manual</code>, <code>partiallyAutomated</code>, or\n<code>fullyAutomated</code>. Default: <code>manual</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Using this resource <em>always</em> implies an override, even if one of\n<code>drs_enabled</code> or <code>drs_automation_level</code> is omitted. Take note of the defaults\nfor both options.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/drs_vm_override.html",docType:""},{id:10,type:"  vsphere_dpm_host_override",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the override in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="host_system_ids"></a><a href="#host_system_ids"><code>host_system_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe host to create the override for.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dpm_enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="dpm_enabled"></a><a href="#dpm_enabled"><code>dpm_enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable DPM support for this host. Default:\n<code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dpm_automation_level",description:'<li><p><a name="dpm_automation_level"></a><a href="#dpm_automation_level"><code>dpm_automation_level</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The automation level for host power\noperations on this host. Can be one of <code>manual</code> or <code>automated</code>. Default:\n<code>manual</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Using this resource <em>always</em> implies an override, even if one of\n<code>dpm_enabled</code> or <code>dpm_automation_level</code> is omitted. Take note of the defaults\nfor both options.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/dpm_host_override.html",docType:""},{id:11,type:"  vsphere_ha_vm_override",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"general-options",description:'<h3 id="general-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#general-options" name="general-options">\xbb</a>\n  General Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options are required:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"compute_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="compute_cluster_id"></a><a href="#compute_cluster_id"><code>compute_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the cluster to put the override in.  Forces a new\nresource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_id",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_id"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_id"><code>virtual_machine_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUID of the virtual machine to create\nthe override for.  Forces a new resource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vsphere-ha-options",description:'<h3 id="vsphere-ha-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vsphere-ha-options" name="vsphere-ha-options">\xbb</a>\n  vSphere HA Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings work nearly in the same fashion as their counterparts in\nthe <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html"><code>vsphere_compute_cluster</code></a> resource, with the\nexception that some options also allow settings that denote the use of cluster\ndefaults. See the individual settings below for more details.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The same version restrictions that apply for certain options\nwithin <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html"><code>vsphere_compute_cluster</code></a> apply to\noverrides as well. See <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">here</a>\nfor an entire list of version restrictions.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"general-ha-options",description:'<h4 id="general-ha-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#general-ha-options" name="general-ha-options">\xbb</a>\n  General HA options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"ha_vm_restart_priority",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The restart priority for the virtual\nmachine when vSphere detects a host failure. Can be one of\n<code>clusterRestartPriority</code>, <code>lowest</code>, <code>low</code>, <code>medium</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>highest</code>.\nDefault: <code>clusterRestartPriority</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_restart_timeout",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum time, in seconds, that\nvSphere HA will wait for this virtual machine to be ready. Use <code>-1</code> to\nspecify the cluster default.  Default: <code>-1</code>.\n<sup><a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_host_isolation_response",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The action to take on this virtual\nmachine when a host has detected that it has been isolated from the rest of\nthe cluster. Can be one of <code>clusterIsolationResponse</code>, <code>none</code>, <code>powerOff</code>, or\n<code>shutdown</code>. Default: <code>clusterIsolationResponse</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings",description:'<h4 id="ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings" name="ha-virtual-machine-component-protection-settings">\xbb</a>\n  HA Virtual Machine Component Protection settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings control Virtual Machine Component Protection (VMCP)\noverrides.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"ha_datastore_pdl_response",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take on this\nvirtual machine when the cluster has detected a permanent device loss to a\nrelevant datastore. Can be one of <code>clusterDefault</code>, <code>disabled</code>, <code>warning</code>, or\n<code>restartAggressive</code>. Default: <code>clusterDefault</code>.\n<sup><a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_response",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take on this\nvirtual machine when the cluster has detected loss to all paths to a relevant\ndatastore. Can be one of <code>clusterDefault</code>, <code>disabled</code>, <code>warning</code>,\n<code>restartConservative</code>, or <code>restartAggressive</code>.  Default: <code>clusterDefault</code>.\n<sup><a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_recovery_action",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the action to take\non this virtual machine if an APD status on an affected datastore clears in\nthe middle of an APD event. Can be one of <code>useClusterDefault</code>, <code>none</code> or\n<code>reset</code>.  Default: <code>useClusterDefault</code>.\n<sup><a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_datastore_apd_response_delay",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the delay in minutes\nto wait after an APD timeout event to execute the response action defined in\n<a href="#ha_datastore_apd_response"><code>ha_datastore_apd_response</code></a>. Use <code>-1</code> to use\nthe cluster default. Default: <code>-1</code>.\n<sup><a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/compute_cluster.html#vsphere-version-requirements">*</a></sup>\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings",description:'<h4 id="ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings" name="ha-virtual-machine-and-application-monitoring-settings">\xbb</a>\n  HA virtual machine and application monitoring settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following settings control virtual machine and application monitoring\noverrides.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">\n<p>Take note of the\n<a href="#ha_vm_monitoring_use_cluster_defaults"><code>ha_vm_monitoring_use_cluster_defaults</code></a>\nsetting - this is defaulted to <code>true</code> and means that override settings are\n<em>not</em> used. Set this to <code>false</code> to ensure your overrides function. Note that\nunlike the rest of the options in this resource, there are no granular\nper-setting cluster default values - <code>ha_vm_monitoring_use_cluster_defaults</code> is\nthe only toggle available.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"ha_vm_monitoring_use_cluster_defaults",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines whether or\nnot the cluster's default settings or the VM override settings specified in\nthis resource are used for virtual machine monitoring. The default is <code>true</code>\n(use cluster defaults)",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_monitoring",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of virtual machine monitoring to use\nwhen HA is enabled in the cluster. Can be one of <code>vmMonitoringDisabled</code>,\n<code>vmMonitoringOnly</code>, or <code>vmAndAppMonitoring</code>. Default: <code>vmMonitoringDisabled</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_failure_interval",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If a heartbeat from this virtual\nmachine is not received within this configured interval, the virtual machine\nis marked as failed. The value is in seconds. Default: <code>30</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_minimum_uptime",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The time, in seconds, that HA waits after\npowering on this virtual machine before monitoring for heartbeats. Default:\n<code>120</code> (2 minutes).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_maximum_resets",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum number of resets that HA will\nperform to this virtual machine when responding to a failure event. Default:\n<code>3</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha_vm_maximum_failure_window",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The length of the reset window in\nwhich <a href="#ha_vm_maximum_resets"><code>ha_vm_maximum_resets</code></a> can operate. When this\nwindow expires, no more resets are attempted regardless of the setting\nconfigured in <code>ha_vm_maximum_resets</code>. <code>-1</code> means no window, meaning an\nunlimited reset time is allotted. The value is specified in seconds. Default:\n<code>-1</code> (no window).\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/ha_vm_override.html",docType:""},{id:12,type:"  vsphere_resource_pool",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the resource pool.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"parent_resource_pool_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a>\nof the parent resource pool. This can be the root resource pool for a cluster\nor standalone host, or a resource pool itself. When moving a resource pool\nfrom one parent resource pool to another, both must share a common root\nresource pool or the move will fail.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU allocation level. The level is a\nsimplified view of shares. Levels map to a pre-determined set of numeric\nvalues for shares. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. When\n<code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>high</code> are specified values in <code>cpu_shares</code> will be\nignored.  Default: <code>normal</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_shares",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of shares allocated for CPU. Used to\ndetermine resource allocation in case of resource contention. If this is set,\n<code>cpu_share_level</code> must be <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Amount of CPU (MHz) that is guaranteed\navailable to the resource pool. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_expandable",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines if the reservation on a resource\npool can grow beyond the specified value if the parent resource pool has\nunreserved resources. Default: <code>true</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU utilization of a resource pool will not exceed\nthis limit, even if there are available resources. Set to <code>-1</code> for unlimited.\nDefault: <code>-1</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU allocation level. The level is a\nsimplified view of shares. Levels map to a pre-determined set of numeric\nvalues for shares. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. When\n<code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>high</code> are specified values in <code>memory_shares</code> will be\nignored.  Default: <code>normal</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_shares",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of shares allocated for CPU. Used to\ndetermine resource allocation in case of resource contention. If this is set,\n<code>memory_share_level</code> must be <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Amount of CPU (MHz) that is guaranteed\navailable to the resource pool. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_expandable",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines if the reservation on a resource\npool can grow beyond the specified value if the parent resource pool has\nunreserved resources. Default: <code>true</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU utilization of a resource pool will not exceed\nthis limit, even if there are available resources. Set to <code>-1</code> for unlimited.\nDefault: <code>-1</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/resource_pool.html",docType:""},{id:13,type:"  vsphere_custom_attribute",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the custom attribute.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"managed_object_type",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The object type that this attribute may be\napplied to. If not set, the custom attribute may be applied to any object\ntype. For a full list, click <a href="#managed-object-types">here</a>. Forces a new\nresource if changed.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"managed-object-types",description:'<h2 id="managed-object-types">\n<a class="anchor" href="#managed-object-types" name="managed-object-types">\xbb</a>\n  Managed Object Types\n</h2>',elementType:"h2"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following table will help you determine what value you need to enter for \nthe managed object type you want the attribute to apply to.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Note that if you want a attribute to apply to all objects, leave the type \nunspecified.</p>",elementType:"p"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html",docType:""},{id:14,type:"  vsphere_datacenter",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datacenter. This name needs to be unique\nwithin the folder. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The folder where the datacenter should be created.\nForces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support is unsupported on direct ESXi connections and\nrequires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to value \nstrings to set for datacenter resource. See \n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values \nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/datacenter.html",docType:""},{id:15,type:"  vsphere_folder",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"path",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The path of the folder to be created. This is relative to\nthe root of the type of folder you are creating, and the supplied datacenter.\nFor example, given a default datacenter of <code>default-dc</code>, a folder of type\n<code>vm</code> (denoting a virtual machine folder), and a supplied folder of\n<code>terraform-test-folder</code>, the resulting path would be\n<code>/default-dc/vm/terraform-test-folder</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>path</code> can be modified - the resulting behavior is dependent on\nwhat section of <code>path</code> you are modifying. If you are modifying the parent (so\nany part before the last <code>/</code>), your folder will be moved to that new parent. If\nmodifying the name (the part after the last <code>/</code>), your folder will be renamed.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"type",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The type of folder to create. Allowed options are\n<code>datacenter</code> for datacenter folders, <code>host</code> for host and cluster folders,\n<code>vm</code> for virtual machine folders, <code>datastore</code> for datastore folders, and\n<code>network</code> for network folders. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter_id",description:"The ID of the datacenter the folder will be created in.\nRequired for all folder types except for datacenter folders. Forces a new\nresource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support is unsupported on direct ESXi connections and\nrequires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute \nvalue strings to set for folder. See <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> \nfor a reference on how to set values for custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/folder.html",docType:""},{id:16,type:"  vsphere_tag",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The display name of the tag. The name must be unique\nwithin its category.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"category_id",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The unique identifier of the parent category in\nwhich this tag will be created. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"description",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A description for the tag.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html",docType:""},{id:17,type:"  vsphere_tag_category",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the category.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cardinality",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The number of tags that can be assigned from this\ncategory to a single object at once. Can be one of <code>SINGLE</code> (object can only\nbe assigned one tag in this category), to <code>MULTIPLE</code> (object can be assigned\nmultiple tags in this category). Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"associable_types",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> A list object types that this category is\nvalid to be assigned to. For a full list, click\n<a href="#associable-object-types">here</a>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"description",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A description for the category.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> You can add associable types to a category, but you cannot remove\nthem. Attempting to do so will result in an error.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"associable-object-types",description:'<h3 id="associable-object-types">\n<a class="anchor" href="#associable-object-types" name="associable-object-types">\xbb</a>\n  Associable Object Types\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following table will help you determine what values you need to enter for\nthe associable type you want to associate with a tag category.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Note that if you want a tag to apply to all objects, the <code>All</code> alias exists -\njust remember that you will not be able to revert this later, and this category\nwill permanently allow all objects.</p>",elementType:"p"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag_category.html",docType:""},{id:18,type:"  vsphere_distributed_port_group",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the port group.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"distributed_virtual_switch_uuid",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The ID of the DVS to add the\nport group to. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"type",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The port group type. Can be one of <code>earlyBinding</code> (static\nbinding) or <code>ephemeral</code>. Default: <code>earlyBinding</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"description",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> An optional description for the port group.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"number_of_ports",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of ports available on this port\ngroup. Cannot be decreased below the amount of used ports on the port group.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"auto_expand",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allows the port group to create additional ports\npast the limit specified in <code>number_of_ports</code> if necessary. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Using <code>auto_expand</code> with a statically defined <code>number_of_ports</code>\nmay lead to errors when the port count grows past the amount specified.  If you\nspecify <code>number_of_ports</code>, you may wish to set <code>auto_expand</code> to <code>false</code>.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"port_name_format",description:'<li><p><a name="port_name_format"></a><a href="#port_name_format"><code>port_name_format</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> An optional formatting policy for naming of\nthe ports in this port group. See the <code>portNameFormat</code> attribute listed\n<a href="https://code.vmware.com/apis/196/vsphere#/doc/vim.dvs.DistributedVirtualPortgroup.ConfigInfo.html#portNameFormat">here</a> for details on the format syntax.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network_resource_pool_key",description:'<li><p><a name="network_resource_pool_key"></a><a href="#network_resource_pool_key"><code>network_resource_pool_key</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The key of a network resource pool\nto associate with this port group. The default is <code>-1</code>, which implies no\nassociation.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<li><p><a name="custom_attributes"></a><a href="#custom_attributes"><code>custom_attributes</code></a> <strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute\nvalue string to set for port group. See <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> \nfor a reference on how to set values for custom attributes.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"policy-options",description:'<h3 id="policy-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#policy-options" name="policy-options">\xbb</a>\n  Policy options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>In addition to the above options, you can configure any policy option that is\navailable under the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#default-port-group-policy-arguments"><code>vsphere_distributed_virtual_switch</code> policy\noptions</a> section. Any policy option that is not set\nis inherited from the DVS, its options propagating to the port group.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>See the link for a full list of options that can be set.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"port-override-options",description:'<h3 id="port-override-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#port-override-options" name="port-override-options">\xbb</a>\n  Port override options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options below control whether or not the policies set in the port\ngroup can be overridden on the individual port:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"block_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#block_all_ports">port shutdown\npolicy</a> to be overridden on an individual port.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"live_port_moving_allowed",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow a port in this port group to be\nmoved to another port group while it is connected.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#netflow_enabled">Netflow\npolicy</a> on this port group to be overridden on an individual\nport.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network_resource_pool_override_allowed",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the network\nresource pool set on this port group to be overridden on an individual port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"port_config_reset_at_disconnect",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Reset a port's settings to the\nsettings defined on this port group policy when the port disconnects.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"security_policy_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#security-options">security policy\nsettings</a> defined in this port group policy to be\noverridden on an individual port.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"shaping_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#traffic-shaping-options">traffic shaping\noptions</a> on this port group policy to be overridden\non an individual port.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"traffic_filter_override_allowed",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow any traffic filters on\nthis port group to be overridden on an individual port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"uplink_teaming_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#ha-policy-options">uplink teaming\noptions</a> on this port group to be overridden on an\nindividual port.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vlan_override_allowed",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html#vlan-options">VLAN settings</a>\non this port group to be overridden on an individual port.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_port_group.html",docType:""},{id:19,type:"  vsphere_distributed_virtual_switch",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the distributed virtual switch.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter_id",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The ID of the datacenter where the distributed\nvirtual switch will be created. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The folder to create the DVS in. Forces a new resource\nif changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"description",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A detailed description for the DVS.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"contact_name",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The name of the person who is responsible for the\nDVS. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"contact_detail",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The detailed contact information for the person\nwho is responsible for the DVS. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv4_address",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> An IPv4 address to identify the switch. This is\nmostly useful when used with the <a href="#netflow-arguments">Netflow arguments</a> found\nbelow.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"lacp_api_version",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The Link Aggregation Control Protocol group\nversion to use with the switch. Possible values are <code>singleLag</code> and\n<code>multipleLag</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"link_discovery_operation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Whether to <code>advertise</code> or <code>listen</code>\nfor link discovery traffic.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"link_discovery_protocol",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The discovery protocol type. Valid\ntypes are <code>cdp</code> and <code>lldp</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"max_mtu",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum transmission unit (MTU) for the virtual\nswitch.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"multicast_filtering_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The multicast filtering mode to use\nwith the switch. Can be one of <code>legacyFiltering</code> or <code>snooping</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"version",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support requires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute\nvalue strings to set for virtual switch. See \n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values \nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"uplink-arguments",description:'<h3 id="uplink-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#uplink-arguments" name="uplink-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  Uplink arguments\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"uplinks",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A list of strings that uniquely identifies the names\nof the uplinks on the DVS across hosts. The number of items in this list\ncontrols the number of uplinks that exist on the DVS, in addition to the\nnames.  See <a href="#uplink-name-and-count-control">here</a> for an example on how to\nuse this option.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host-management-arguments",description:'<h3 id="host-management-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#host-management-arguments" name="host-management-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  Host management arguments\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"list description",description:'<a name="host"></a>',elementType:"p"},{name:"host_system_id",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The host system ID of the host to add to the\nDVS.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:2},{name:"devices",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The list of NIC devices to map to uplinks on the DVS,\nadded in order they are specified.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:2},{name:"netflow-arguments",description:'<h3 id="netflow-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#netflow-arguments" name="netflow-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  Netflow arguments\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control settings that you can use to configure Netflow on\nthe DVS:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"netflow_active_flow_timeout",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of seconds after which\nactive flows are forced to be exported to the collector. Allowed range is\n<code>60</code> to <code>3600</code>. Default: <code>60</code>. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_collector_ip_address",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> IP address for the Netflow\ncollector, using IPv4 or IPv6. IPv6 is supported in vSphere Distributed\nSwitch Version 6.0 or later. Must be set before Netflow can be enabled.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_collector_port",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Port for the Netflow collector. This\nmust be set before Netflow can be enabled.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_idle_flow_timeout",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of seconds after which\nidle flows are forced to be exported to the collector. Allowed range is <code>10</code>\nto <code>600</code>. Default: <code>15</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_internal_flows_only",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Whether to limit analysis to\ntraffic that has both source and destination served by the same host.\nDefault: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_observation_domain_id",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The observation domain ID for\nthe Netflow collector.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_sampling_rate",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The ratio of total number of packets to\nthe number of packets analyzed. The default is <code>0</code>, which indicates that the\nswitch should analyze all packets. The maximum value is <code>1000</code>, which\nindicates an analysis rate of 0.001%.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network-i-o-control-arguments",description:'<h3 id="network-i-o-control-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#network-i-o-control-arguments" name="network-i-o-control-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  Network I/O control arguments\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments manage network I/O control. Network I/O control (also\nknown as network resource control) can be used to set up advanced traffic\nshaping for the DVS, allowing control of various classes of traffic in a\nfashion similar to how resource pools work for virtual machines. Configuration\nof network I/O control is also a requirement for the use of network resource\npools, if their use is so desired.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"general-network-i-o-control-arguments",description:'<h4 id="general-network-i-o-control-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#general-network-i-o-control-arguments" name="general-network-i-o-control-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  General network I/O control arguments\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"network_resource_control_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Set to <code>true</code> to enable\nnetwork I/O control. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network_resource_control_version",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The version of network I/O\ncontrol to use. Can be one of <code>version2</code> or <code>version3</code>. Default: <code>version2</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network-i-o-control-traffic-classes",description:'<h4 id="network-i-o-control-traffic-classes">\n<a class="anchor" href="#network-i-o-control-traffic-classes" name="network-i-o-control-traffic-classes">\xbb</a>\n  Network I/O control traffic classes\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>There are currently 9 traffic classes that can be used for network I/O\ncontrol - they are below.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Each of these classes has 4 options that can be tuned that are discussed in the\nnext section.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"traffic-class-resource-options",description:'<h4 id="traffic-class-resource-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#traffic-class-resource-options" name="traffic-class-resource-options">\xbb</a>\n  Traffic class resource options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>There are 4 traffic resource options for each class, prefixed with the name of\nthe traffic classes seen above.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>For example, to set the traffic class resource options for virtual machine\ntraffic, see the example below:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_distributed_virtual_switch"</span> <span class="s2">"dvs"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n  <span class="n">virtualmachine_share_level</span>      <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"custom"</span>\n  <span class="n">virtualmachine_share_count</span>      <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">150</span>\n  <span class="n">virtualmachine_maximum_mbit</span>     <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">200</span>\n  <span class="n">virtualmachine_reservation_mbit</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">20</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A pre-defined share level that can be assigned to\nthis resource class. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"share_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of shares for a custom level. This is\nignored if <code>share_level</code> is not <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"maximum_mbit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum amount of bandwidth allowed for this\ntraffic class in Mbits/sec.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"reservation_mbit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The guaranteed amount of bandwidth for this\ntraffic class in Mbits/sec.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"default-port-group-policy-arguments",description:'<h3 id="default-port-group-policy-arguments">\n<a class="anchor" href="#default-port-group-policy-arguments" name="default-port-group-policy-arguments">\xbb</a>\n  Default port group policy arguments\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following arguments are shared with the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_port_group.html"><code>vsphere_distributed_port_group</code></a> resource. Setting\nthem here defines a default policy here that will be inherited by other port\ngroups on this switch that do not have these values otherwise overridden. Not\ndefining these options in a DVS will infer defaults that can be seen in the\nTerraform state after the initial apply.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<p>Of particular note to a DVS are the <a href="#ha-policy-options">HA policy options</a>,\nwhich is where the <code>active_uplinks</code> and <code>standby_uplinks</code> options are\ncontrolled, allowing the ability to create a NIC failover policy that applies\nto the entire DVS and all portgroups within it that don\'t override the policy.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"vlan-options",description:'<h4 id="vlan-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vlan-options" name="vlan-options">\xbb</a>\n  VLAN options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control the VLAN behaviour of the port groups the port\npolicy applies to. One one of these 3 options may be set:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"vlan",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The member VLAN for the ports this policy applies to. A\nvalue of <code>0</code> means no VLAN.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vlan_range",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Used to denote VLAN trunking. Use the <code>min_vlan</code>\nand <code>max_vlan</code> sub-arguments to define the tagged VLAN range. Multiple\n<code>vlan_range</code> definitions are allowed, but they must not overlap. Example\nbelow:\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_distributed_virtual_switch"</span> <span class="s2">"dvs"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n  <span class="n">vlan_range</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">min_vlan</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>\n    <span class="n">max_vlan</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1000</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="n">vlan_range</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">min_vlan</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">2000</span>\n    <span class="n">max_vlan</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">4094</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"port_private_secondary_vlan_id",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Used to define a secondary VLAN\nID when using private VLANs.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ha-policy-options",description:'<h4 id="ha-policy-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#ha-policy-options" name="ha-policy-options">\xbb</a>\n  HA policy options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control HA policy for ports that this policy applies to:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"active_uplinks",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A list of active uplinks to be used in load\nbalancing. These uplinks need to match the definitions in the\n<a href="#uplinks"><code>uplinks</code></a> DVS argument. See\n<a href="#uplink-name-and-count-control">here</a> for more details.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"standby_uplinks",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A list of standby uplinks to be used in\nfailover. These uplinks need to match the definitions in the\n<a href="#uplinks"><code>uplinks</code></a> DVS argument. See\n<a href="#uplink-name-and-count-control">here</a> for more details.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"check_beacon",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enables beacon probing as an additional measure\nto detect NIC failure.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> VMware recommends using a minimum of 3 NICs when using beacon\nprobing.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"failback",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If <code>true</code>, the teaming policy will re-activate failed\nuplinks higher in precedence when they come back up.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"notify_switches",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If <code>true</code>, the teaming policy will notify the\nbroadcast network of an uplink failover, triggering cache updates.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"teaming_policy",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The uplink teaming policy. Can be one of\n<code>loadbalance_ip</code>, <code>loadbalance_srcmac</code>, <code>loadbalance_srcid</code>, or\n<code>failover_explicit</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"lacp-options",description:'<h4 id="lacp-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#lacp-options" name="lacp-options">\xbb</a>\n  LACP options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options allow the use of LACP for NIC teaming for ports that this\npolicy applies to.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> These options are ignored for non-uplink port groups and hence are\nonly useful at the DVS level.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"lacp_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enables LACP for the ports that this policy\napplies to.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"lacp_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The LACP mode. Can be one of <code>active</code> or <code>passive</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"security-options",description:'<h4 id="security-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#security-options" name="security-options">\xbb</a>\n  Security options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control security settings for the ports that this policy\napplies to:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"allow_forged_transmits",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls whether or not a virtual\nnetwork adapter is allowed to send network traffic with a different MAC\naddress than that of its own.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"allow_mac_changes",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls whether or not the Media Access\nControl (MAC) address can be changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"allow_promiscuous",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable promiscuous mode on the network. This\nflag indicates whether or not all traffic is seen on a given port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"traffic-shaping-options",description:'<h4 id="traffic-shaping-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#traffic-shaping-options" name="traffic-shaping-options">\xbb</a>\n  Traffic shaping options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control traffic shaping settings for the ports that this\npolicy applies to:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"ingress_shaping_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> <code>true</code> if the traffic shaper is\nenabled on the port for ingress traffic.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ingress_shaping_average_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The average bandwidth in\nbits per second if ingress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ingress_shaping_peak_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The peak bandwidth during\nbursts in bits per second if ingress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ingress_shaping_burst_size",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum burst size allowed in\nbytes if ingress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"egress_shaping_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> <code>true</code> if the traffic shaper is enabled\non the port for egress traffic.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"egress_shaping_average_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The average bandwidth in bits\nper second if egress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"egress_shaping_peak_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The peak bandwidth during bursts\nin bits per second if egress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"egress_shaping_burst_size",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum burst size allowed in\nbytes if egress traffic shaping is enabled on the port.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"miscellaneous-options",description:'<h4 id="miscellaneous-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#miscellaneous-options" name="miscellaneous-options">\xbb</a>\n  Miscellaneous options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following are some general options that also affect ports that this policy\napplies to:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"block_all_ports",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Shuts down all ports in the port groups that\nthis policy applies to, effectively blocking all network access to connected\nvirtual devices.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"netflow_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enables Netflow on all ports that this policy\napplies to.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tx_uplink",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Forward all traffic transmitted by ports for which\nthis policy applies to its DVS uplinks.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"directpath_gen2_allowed",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow VMDirectPath Gen2 for the ports\nfor which this policy applies to.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/distributed_virtual_switch.html",docType:""},{id:20,type:"  vsphere_host_port_group",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the port group.  Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe host to set the port group up on. Forces a new resource if changed.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_switch_name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the virtual switch to bind\nthis port group to. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vlan_id",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The VLAN ID/trunk mode for this port group.  An ID of\n<code>0</code> denotes no tagging, an ID of <code>1</code>-<code>4094</code> tags with the specific ID, and an\nID of <code>4095</code> enables trunk mode, allowing the guest to manage its own\ntagging. Default: <code>0</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"policy-options",description:'<h3 id="policy-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#policy-options" name="policy-options">\xbb</a>\n  Policy Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>In addition to the above options, you can configure any policy option that is\navailable under the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/host_virtual_switch.html#policy-options"><code>vsphere_host_virtual_switch</code> policy options\nsection</a>.  Any policy option that is not set is\n<strong>inherited</strong> from the virtual switch, its options propagating to the port\ngroup.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>See the link for a full list of options that can be set.</p>",elementType:"p"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/host_port_group.html",docType:""},{id:21,type:"  vsphere_host_virtual_switch",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the virtual switch. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe host to set the virtual switch up on. Forces a new resource if changed.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mtu",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum transmission unit (MTU) for the virtual\nswitch. Default: <code>1500</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"number_of_ports",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of ports to create with this\nvirtual switch. Default: <code>128</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Changing the port count requires a reboot of the host. Terraform\nwill not restart the host for you.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"bridge-options",description:'<h3 id="bridge-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#bridge-options" name="bridge-options">\xbb</a>\n  Bridge Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are related to how the virtual switch binds to physical\nNICs:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"network_adapters",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The network interfaces to bind to the bridge.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"beacon_interval",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The interval, in seconds, that a NIC beacon\npacket is sent out. This can be used with <a href="#check_beacon"><code>check_beacon</code></a> to\noffer link failure capability beyond link status only. Default: <code>1</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"link_discovery_operation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Whether to <code>advertise</code> or <code>listen</code>\nfor link discovery traffic. Default: <code>listen</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"link_discovery_protocol",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The discovery protocol type.  Valid\ntypes are <code>cpd</code> and <code>lldp</code>. Default: <code>cdp</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"policy-options",description:'<h3 id="policy-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#policy-options" name="policy-options">\xbb</a>\n  Policy Options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following options relate to how network traffic is handled on this virtual\nswitch. It also controls the NIC failover order. This subset of options is\nshared with the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/host_port_group.html"><code>vsphere_host_port_group</code></a> resource, in which\noptions can be omitted to ensure options are inherited from the switch\nconfiguration here.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"nic-teaming-options",description:'<h4 id="nic-teaming-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#nic-teaming-options" name="nic-teaming-options">\xbb</a>\n  NIC Teaming Options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE on NIC failover order:</strong> An adapter can be in <code>active_nics</code>,\n<code>standby_nics</code>, or neither to flag it as unused. However, virtual switch\ncreation or update operations will fail if a NIC is present in both settings,\nor if the NIC is not a valid NIC in <code>network_adapters</code>.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> VMware recommends using a minimum of 3 NICs when using beacon\nprobing (configured with <a href="#check_beacon"><code>check_beacon</code></a>).</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"active_nics",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The list of active network adapters used for load\nbalancing.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"standby_nics",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The list of standby network adapters used for\nfailover.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"check_beacon",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable beacon probing",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"teaming_policy",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The network adapter teaming policy. Can be one\nof <code>loadbalance_ip</code>, <code>loadbalance_srcmac</code>, <code>loadbalance_srcid</code>, or\n<code>failover_explicit</code>. Default: <code>loadbalance_srcid</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"notify_switches",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, the teaming policy will\nnotify the broadcast network of a NIC failover, triggering cache updates.\nDefault: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"failback",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, the teaming policy will re-activate\nfailed interfaces higher in precedence when they come back up.  Default:\n<code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"security-policy-options",description:'<h4 id="security-policy-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#security-policy-options" name="security-policy-options">\xbb</a>\n  Security Policy Options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"allow_promiscuous",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable promiscuous mode on the network. This\nflag indicates whether or not all traffic is seen on a given port. Default:\n<code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"allow_forged_transmits",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls whether or not the virtual\nnetwork adapter is allowed to send network traffic with a different MAC\naddress than that of its own. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"allow_mac_changes",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls whether or not the Media Access\nControl (MAC) address can be changed. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"traffic-shaping-options",description:'<h4 id="traffic-shaping-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#traffic-shaping-options" name="traffic-shaping-options">\xbb</a>\n  Traffic Shaping Options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"shaping_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Set to <code>true</code> to enable the traffic shaper for\nports managed by this virtual switch. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"shaping_average_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The average bandwidth in bits per\nsecond if traffic shaping is enabled. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"shaping_peak_bandwidth",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The peak bandwidth during bursts in\nbits per second if traffic shaping is enabled. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"shaping_burst_size",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum burst size allowed in bytes if\nshaping is enabled. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/host_virtual_switch.html",docType:""},{id:22,type:"  vsphere_datastore_cluster",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datastore cluster.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe datacenter to create the datastore cluster in. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The relative path to a folder to put this datastore\ncluster in.  This is a path relative to the datacenter you are deploying the\ndatastore to.  Example: for the <code>dc1</code> datacenter, and a provided <code>folder</code> of\n<code>foo/bar</code>, Terraform will place a datastore cluster named\n<code>terraform-datastore-cluster-test</code> in a datastore folder located at\n<code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar</code>, with the final inventory path being\n<code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar/terraform-datastore-cluster-test</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable Storage DRS for this datastore cluster.\nDefault: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support requires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A map of custom attribute ids to attribute\nvalue strings to set for the datastore cluster. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values\nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"storage-drs-automation-options",description:'<h3 id="storage-drs-automation-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-drs-automation-options" name="storage-drs-automation-options">\xbb</a>\n  Storage DRS automation options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control the automation levels for Storage DRS on the\ndatastore cluster.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>All options below can either be one of two settings: <code>manual</code> for manual mode,\nwhere Storage DRS makes migration recommendations but does not execute them, or\n<code>automated</code> for fully automated mode, where Storage DRS executes migration\nrecommendations automatically.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The automation level can be further tuned for each specific SDRS subsystem.\nSpecifying an override will set the automation level for that part of Storage\nDRS to the respective level. Not specifying an override infers that you want to\nuse the cluster default automation level.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"sdrs_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The global automation level for all\nvirtual machines in this datastore cluster. Default: <code>manual</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_space_balance_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default\nautomation settings when correcting disk space imbalances.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_balance_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default\nautomation settings when correcting I/O load imbalances.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_rule_enforcement_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default\nautomation settings when correcting affinity rule violations.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_policy_enforcement_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default\nautomation settings when correcting storage and VM policy violations.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_vm_evacuation_automation_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default\nautomation settings when generating recommendations for datastore evacuation.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"storage-drs-i-o-load-balancing-settings",description:'<h3 id="storage-drs-i-o-load-balancing-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-drs-i-o-load-balancing-settings" name="storage-drs-i-o-load-balancing-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Storage DRS I/O load balancing settings\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control I/O load balancing for Storage DRS on the\ndatastore cluster.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> All reservable IOPS settings require vSphere 6.0 or higher and are\nignored on older versions.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"sdrs_io_load_balance_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable I/O load balancing for\nthis datastore cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_latency_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The I/O latency threshold, in\nmilliseconds, that storage DRS uses to make recommendations to move disks\nfrom this datastore. Default: <code>15</code> seconds.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_load_imbalance_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The difference between load\nin datastores in the cluster before storage DRS makes recommendations to\nbalance the load. Default: <code>5</code> percent.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_reservable_iops_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The threshold of reservable\nIOPS of all virtual machines on the datastore before storage DRS makes\nrecommendations to move VMs off of a datastore. Note that this setting should\nonly be set if <code>sdrs_io_reservable_percent_threshold</code> cannot make an accurate\nestimate of the capacity of the datastores in your cluster, and should be set\nto roughly 50-60% of the worst case peak performance of the backing LUNs.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_reservable_percent_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The threshold, in\npercent, of actual estimated performance of the datastore (in IOPS) that\nstorage DRS uses to make recommendations to move VMs off of a datastore when\nthe total reservable IOPS exceeds the threshold. Default: <code>60</code> percent.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_io_reservable_threshold_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The reservable IOPS\nthreshold setting to use, <code>sdrs_io_reservable_percent_threshold</code> in the event\nof <code>automatic</code>, or <code>sdrs_io_reservable_iops_threshold</code> in the event of\n<code>manual</code>. Default: <code>automatic</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"storage-drs-disk-space-load-balancing-settings",description:'<h3 id="storage-drs-disk-space-load-balancing-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-drs-disk-space-load-balancing-settings" name="storage-drs-disk-space-load-balancing-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Storage DRS disk space load balancing settings\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control disk space load balancing for Storage DRS on the\ndatastore cluster.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Setting <code>sdrs_free_space_threshold_mode</code> to <code>freeSpace</code> and using\nthe <code>sdrs_free_space_threshold</code> setting requires vSphere 6.0 or higher and is\nignored on older versions. Using these settings on older versions may result in\nspurious diffs in Terraform.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"sdrs_free_space_utilization_difference",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The threshold, in\npercent of used space, that storage DRS uses to make decisions to migrate VMs\nout of a datastore. Default: <code>80</code> percent.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_free_space_utilization_difference",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The threshold, in\npercent, of difference between space utilization in datastores before storage\nDRS makes decisions to balance the space. Default: <code>5</code> percent.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_free_space_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The threshold, in GB, that storage\nDRS uses to make decisions to migrate VMs out of a datastore. Default: <code>50</code>\nGB.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_free_space_threshold",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The free space threshold to use.\nWhen set to <code>utilization</code>, <code>drs_space_utilization_threshold</code> is used, and\nwhen set to <code>freeSpace</code>, <code>drs_free_space_threshold</code> is used. Default:\n<code>utilization</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"storage-drs-advanced-settings",description:'<h3 id="storage-drs-advanced-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-drs-advanced-settings" name="storage-drs-advanced-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Storage DRS advanced settings\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control advanced parts of Storage DRS that may not\nrequire changing during basic operation:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"sdrs_default_intra_vm_affinity",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> When <code>true</code>, all disks in a\nsingle virtual machine will be kept on the same datastore. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_load_balance_interval",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The storage DRS poll interval, in\nminutes. Default: <code>480</code> minutes.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_advanced_options",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A key/value map of advanced Storage DRS\nsettings that are not exposed via Terraform or the vSphere client.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/datastore_cluster.html",docType:""},{id:23,type:"  vsphere_datastore_cluster_vm_anti_affinity_rule",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="datastore_cluster_id"></a><a href="#datastore_cluster_id"><code>datastore_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the datastore cluster to put the group in.  Forces\na new resource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"name",description:'<li><p><a name="name"></a><a href="#name"><code>name</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the rule. This must be unique in the cluster.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_ids",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_ids"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_ids"><code>virtual_machine_ids</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUIDs of the virtual machines to run\non different datastores from each other.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The minimum length of <code>virtual_machine_ids</code> is 2, and due to\ncurrent limitations in Terraform Core, the value is currently checked during\nthe apply phase, not the validation or plan phases. Ensure proper length of\nthis value to prevent failures mid-apply.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable this rule in the cluster. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mandatory",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> When this value is <code>true</code>, prevents any virtual\nmachine operations that may violate this rule. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/datastore_cluster_vm_anti_affinity_rule.html",docType:""},{id:24,type:"  vsphere_file",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>If <code>source_datacenter</code> and <code>source_datastore</code> are not provided, the file\nresource will upload the file from the host that Terraform is running on. If\neither <code>source_datacenter</code> or <code>source_datastore</code> are provided, the resource\nwill copy from within specified locations in vSphere.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"source_file",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The path to the file being uploaded from the\nTerraform host to vSphere or copied within vSphere. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"destination_file",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The path to where the file should be uploaded\nor copied to on vSphere.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"source_datacenter",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The name of a datacenter in which the file\nwill be copied from. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The name of a datacenter in which the file will be\nuploaded to.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"source_datastore",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The name of the datastore in which file will\nbe copied from. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datastore in which to upload the\nfile to.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"create_directories",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Create directories in <code>destination_file</code>\npath parameter if any missing for copy operation. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Any directory created as part of the operation when\n<code>create_directories</code> is enabled will not be deleted when the resource is\ndestroyed.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/file.html",docType:""},{id:25,type:"  vsphere_nas_datastore",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datastore. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_ids",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object IDs</a> of\nthe hosts to mount the datastore on.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"type",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of NAS volume. Can be one of <code>NFS</code> (to denote\nv3) or <code>NFS41</code> (to denote NFS v4.1). Default: <code>NFS</code>. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"remote_hosts",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The hostnames or IP addresses of the remote\nserver or servers. Only one element should be present for NFS v3 but multiple\ncan be present for NFS v4.1. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"remote_path",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The remote path of the mount point. Forces a new\nresource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"access_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Access mode for the mount point. Can be one of\n<code>readOnly</code> or <code>readWrite</code>. Note that <code>readWrite</code> does not necessarily mean\nthat the datastore will be read-write depending on the permissions of the\nactual share. Default: <code>readWrite</code>. Forces a new resource if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"security_type",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The security type to use when using NFS v4.1.\nCan be one of <code>AUTH_SYS</code>, <code>SEC_KRB5</code>, or <code>SEC_KRB5I</code>. Forces a new resource\nif changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The relative path to a folder to put this datastore in.\nThis is a path relative to the datacenter you are deploying the datastore to.\nExample: for the <code>dc1</code> datacenter, and a provided <code>folder</code> of <code>foo/bar</code>,\nTerraform will place a datastore named <code>terraform-test</code> in a datastore folder\nlocated at <code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar</code>, with the final inventory path being\n<code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar/terraform-test</code>. Conflicts with\n<code>datastore_cluster_id</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object\nID</a> of a datastore cluster to put this datastore in.\nConflicts with <code>folder</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support is unsupported on direct ESXi connections and\nrequires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute \nvalue strings to set on datasource resource. See \n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values \nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/nas_datastore.html",docType:""},{id:26,type:"  vsphere_storage_drs_vm_override",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:'<li><p><a name="datastore_cluster_id"></a><a href="#datastore_cluster_id"><code>datastore_cluster_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the datastore cluster to put the override in.\nForces a new resource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual_machine_id",description:'<li><p><a name="virtual_machine_id"></a><a href="#virtual_machine_id"><code>virtual_machine_id</code></a> - <strong>(Required)</strong> The UUID of the virtual machine to create\nthe override for.  Forces a new resource if changed.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_enabled",description:'<li><p><a name="sdrs_enabled"></a><a href="#sdrs_enabled"><code>sdrs_enabled</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the default Storage DRS setting for\nthis virtual machine. When not specified, the datastore cluster setting is\nused.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_automation_level",description:'<li><p><a name="sdrs_automation_level"></a><a href="#sdrs_automation_level"><code>sdrs_automation_level</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides any Storage DRS automation\nlevels for this virtual machine. Can be one of <code>automated</code> or <code>manual</code>. When\nnot specified, the datastore cluster\'s settings are used according to the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/datastore_cluster.html#storage-drs-automation-options">specific SDRS subsystem</a>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"sdrs_intra_vm_affinity",description:'<li><p><a name="sdrs_intra_vm_affinity"></a><a href="#sdrs_intra_vm_affinity"><code>sdrs_intra_vm_affinity</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Overrides the intra-VM affinity setting\nfor this virtual machine. When <code>true</code>, all disks for this virtual machine\nwill be kept on the same datastore. When <code>false</code>, Storage DRS may locate\nindividual disks on different datastores if it helps satisfy cluster\nrequirements. When not specified, the datastore cluster\'s settings are used.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/storage_drs_vm_override.html",docType:""},{id:27,type:"  vsphere_vmfs_datastore",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datastore. Forces a new resource if\nchanged.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe host to set the datastore up on. Note that this is not necessarily the\nonly host that the datastore will be set up on',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disks",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The disks to use with the datastore.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The relative path to a folder to put this datastore in.\nThis is a path relative to the datacenter you are deploying the datastore to.\nExample: for the <code>dc1</code> datacenter, and a provided <code>folder</code> of <code>foo/bar</code>,\nTerraform will place a datastore named <code>terraform-test</code> in a datastore folder\nlocated at <code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar</code>, with the final inventory path being\n<code>/dc1/datastore/foo/bar/terraform-test</code>. Conflicts with\n<code>datastore_cluster_id</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object\nID</a> of a datastore cluster to put this datastore in.\nConflicts with <code>folder</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support is unsupported on direct ESXi connections and\nrequires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:' <strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute \nvalue string to set on datastore resource. See \n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values \nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/vmfs_datastore.html",docType:""},{id:28,type:"  vsphere_virtual_disk",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> All fields in the <code>vsphere_virtual_disk</code> resource are currently\nimmutable and force a new resource if changed.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"vmdk_path",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The path, including filename, of the virtual disk to\nbe created.  This needs to end in <code>.vmdk</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the datastore in which to create the\ndisk.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"size",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> Size of the disk (in GB).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datacenter",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The name of the datacenter in which to create the\ndisk. Can be omitted when when ESXi or if there is only one datacenter in\nyour infrastructure.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"type",description:'<li><p><a name="type"></a><a href="#type"><code>type</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of disk to create. Can be one of\n<code>eagerZeroedThick</code>, <code>lazy</code>, or <code>thin</code>. Default: <code>eagerZeroedThick</code>. For\ninformation on what each kind of disk provisioning policy means, click\n<a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-4C0F4D73-82F2-4B81-8AA7-1DD752A8A5AC.html">here</a>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"adapter_type",description:'<li><p><a name="adapter_type"></a><a href="#adapter_type"><code>adapter_type</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The adapter type for this virtual disk. Can be\none of <code>ide</code>, <code>lsiLogic</code>, or <code>busLogic</code>.  Default: <code>lsiLogic</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>adapter_type</code> is <strong>deprecated</strong>: it does not dictate the type of\ncontroller that the virtual disk will be attached to on the virtual machine.\nPlease see the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/virtual_machine.html#scsi_type"><code>scsi_type</code></a> parameter\nin the <code>vsphere_virtual_machine</code> resource for information on how to control\ndisk controller types. This parameter will be removed in future versions of the\nvSphere provider.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"create_directories",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Tells the resource to create any\ndirectories that are a part of the <code>vmdk_path</code> parameter if they are missing.\nDefault: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Any directory created as part of the operation when\n<code>create_directories</code> is enabled will not be deleted when the resource is\ndestroyed.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/virtual_disk.html",docType:""},{id:29,type:"  vsphere_virtual_machine",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"general-options",description:'<h3 id="general-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#general-options" name="general-options">\xbb</a>\n  General options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options are general virtual machine and Terraform workflow\noptions:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"resource_pool_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the resource pool to put this virtual machine in.\nSee the section on <a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual machine migration</a>\nfor details on changing this value.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> All clusters and standalone hosts have a resource pool, even if\none has not been explicitly created. For more information, see the section on\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/d/resource_pool.html#specifying-the-root-resource-pool-for-a-standalone-host">specifying the root resource pool </a> in the\n<code>vsphere_resource_pool</code> data source documentation. This resource does not take\na cluster or standalone host resource directly.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"datastore_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the virtual machine\'s datastore. The virtual\nmachine configuration is placed here, along with any virtual disks that are\ncreated where a datastore is not explicitly specified. See the section on\n<a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual machine migration</a> for details on\nchanging this value.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the datastore cluster ID to use. This setting\napplies to entire virtual machine and implies that you wish to use Storage\nDRS with this virtual machine. See the section on <a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual machine\nmigration</a> for details on changing this value.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> One of <code>datastore_id</code> or <code>datastore_cluster_id</code> must be specified.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Use of <code>datastore_cluster_id</code> requires Storage DRS to be enabled\non that cluster.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The <code>datastore_cluster_id</code> setting applies to the entire virtual\nmachine - you cannot assign individual datastore clusters to individual disks.\nIn addition to this, you cannot use the <a href="#attach"><code>attach</code></a> setting to attach\nexternal disks on virtual machines that are assigned to datastore clusters.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"folder",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The path to the folder to put this virtual machine in,\nrelative to the datacenter that the resource pool is in.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"host_system_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> An optional <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of a host to put this virtual machine on. See the\nsection on <a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual machine migration</a> for\ndetails on changing this value. If a <code>host_system_id</code> is not supplied,\nvSphere will select a host in the resource pool to place the virtual machine,\naccording to any defaults or DRS policies in place. \n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disk",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> A specification for a virtual disk device on this virtual\nmachine. See <a href="#disk-options">disk options</a> below.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network_interface",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> A specification for a virtual NIC on this\nvirtual machine. See <a href="#network-interface-options">network interface options</a>\nbelow.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cdrom",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A specification for a CDROM device on this virtual\nmachine. See <a href="#cdrom-options">CDROM options</a> below.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"clone",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> When specified, the VM will be created as a clone of a\nspecified template. Optional customization options can be submitted as well.\nSee <a href="#creating-a-virtual-machine-from-a-template">creating a virtual machine from a\ntemplate</a> for more details.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Cloning requires vCenter and is not supported on direct ESXi\nconnections.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"vapp",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Optional vApp configuration. The only sub-key available\nis <code>properties</code>, which is a key/value map of properties for virtual machines\nimported from OVF or OVA files. See <a href="#using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration">Using vApp properties to supply OVF/OVA\nconfiguration</a> for\nmore details.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"guest_id",description:'<li><p><a name="guest_id"></a><a href="#guest_id"><code>guest_id</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The guest ID for the operating system type. For a\nfull list of possible values, see <a href="https://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-6-5/topic/com.vmware.wssdk.apiref.doc/vim.vm.GuestOsDescriptor.GuestOsIdentifier.html">here</a>. Default: <code>other-64</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"alternate_guest_name",description:'<li><p><a name="alternate_guest_name"></a><a href="#alternate_guest_name"><code>alternate_guest_name</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The guest name for the operating system\nwhen <code>guest_id</code> is <code>other</code> or <code>other-64</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"annotation",description:'<li><p><a name="annotation"></a><a href="#annotation"><code>annotation</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> A user-provided description of the virtual machine.\nThe default is no annotation.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"firmware",description:'<li><p><a name="firmware"></a><a href="#firmware"><code>firmware</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The firmware interface to use on the virtual machine.\nCan be one of <code>bios</code> or <code>EFI</code>. Default: <code>bios</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"extra_config",description:'<li><p><a name="extra_config"></a><a href="#extra_config"><code>extra_config</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> Extra configuration data for this virtual\nmachine. Can be used to supply advanced parameters not normally in\nconfiguration, such as instance metadata.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Do not use <code>extra_config</code> when working with a template imported\nfrom OVF or OVA as more than likely your settings will be ignored. Use the\n<code>vapp</code> block\'s <code>properties</code> section as outlined in <a href="#using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration">Using vApp properties to\nsupply OVF/OVA\nconfiguration</a>.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"scsi_type",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The type of SCSI bus this virtual machine will have.\nCan be one of lsilogic (LSI Logic Parallel), lsilogic-sas (LSI Logic SAS) or\npvscsi (VMware Paravirtual). Defualt: <code>pvscsi</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"scsi_bus_sharing",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Mode for sharing the SCSI bus. The modes are\nphysicalSharing, virtualSharing, and noSharing. Default: <code>noSharing</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Tagging support is unsupported on direct ESXi connections and\nrequires vCenter 6.0 or higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"custom_attributes",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Map of custom attribute ids to attribute\nvalue strings to set for virtual machine. See \n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/custom_attribute.html#using-custom-attributes-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to set values \nfor custom attributes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Custom attributes are unsupported on direct ESXi connections \nand require vCenter.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"cpu-and-memory-options",description:'<h3 id="cpu-and-memory-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#cpu-and-memory-options" name="cpu-and-memory-options">\xbb</a>\n  CPU and memory options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control CPU and memory settings on the virtual machine:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"num_cpus",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The total number of virtual processor cores to assign\nto this virtual machine. Default: <code>1</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"num_cores_per_socket",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of cores per socket in this\nvirtual machine. The number of vCPUs on the virtual machine will be\n<code>num_cpus</code> divided by <code>num_cores_per_socket</code>. If specified, the value\nsupplied to <code>num_cpus</code> must be evenly divisible by this value. Default: <code>1</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_hot_add_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow CPUs to be added to this virtual\nmachine while it is running.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_hot_remove_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow CPUs to be removed to this\nvirtual machine while it is running.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The size of the virtual machine's memory, in MB.\nDefault: <code>1024</code> (1 GB).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_hot_add_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Allow memory to be added to this\nvirtual machine while it is running.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Certain CPU and memory hot-plug options are not available on every\noperating system. Check the <a href="http://partnerweb.vmware.com/comp_guide2/pdf/VMware_GOS_Compatibility_Guide.pdf">VMware Guest OS Compatibility\nGuide</a> first to see what settings your guest\noperating system is eligible for. In addition, at least one <code>terraform apply</code>\nmust be executed before being able to take advantage of CPU and memory hot-plug\nsettings, so if you want the support, enable it as soon as possible.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"boot-options",description:'<h3 id="boot-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#boot-options" name="boot-options">\xbb</a>\n  Boot options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control boot settings on the virtual machine:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"boot_delay",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of milliseconds to wait before starting\nthe boot sequence. The default is no delay.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"efi_secure_boot_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> When the <code>firmware</code> type is set to is\n<code>efi</code>, this enables EFI secure boot. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> EFI secure boot is only available on vSphere 6.5 and higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"boot_retry_delay",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of milliseconds to wait before\nretrying the boot sequence. This only valid if <code>boot_retry_enabled</code> is true.\nDefault: <code>10000</code> (10 seconds).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"boot_retry_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to true, a virtual machine that\nfails to boot will try again after the delay defined in <code>boot_retry_delay</code>.\nDefault: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"vmware-tools-options",description:'<h3 id="vmware-tools-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#vmware-tools-options" name="vmware-tools-options">\xbb</a>\n  VMware Tools options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control VMware tools options on the virtual machine:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"sync_time_with_host",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable guest clock synchronization with\nthe host. Requires VMware tools to be installed. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_tools_scripts_after_power_on",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable the execution of\npost-power-on scripts when VMware tools is installed. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_tools_scripts_after_resume",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable the execution of\npost-resume scripts when VMware tools is installed. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_tools_scripts_before_guest_reboot",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable the execution of\npre-reboot scripts when VMware tools is installed. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_tools_scripts_before_guest_shutdown",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable the execution\nof pre-shutdown scripts when VMware tools is installed. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_tools_scripts_before_guest_standby",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable the execution of\npre-standby scripts when VMware tools is installed. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"resource-allocation-options",description:'<h3 id="resource-allocation-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#resource-allocation-options" name="resource-allocation-options">\xbb</a>\n  Resource allocation options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options allow control over CPU and memory allocation on the\nvirtual machine. Note that the resource pool that this VM is in may affect\nthese options.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"cpu_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum amount of CPU (in MHz) that this virtual\nmachine can consume, regardless of available resources. The default is no\nlimit.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of CPU (in MHz) that this virtual\nmachine is guaranteed. The default is no reservation.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The allocation level for CPU resources. Can be\none of <code>high</code>, <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>custom</code>. Default: <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_share_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of CPU shares allocated to the\nvirtual machine when the <code>cpu_share_level</code> is <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The maximum amount of memory (in MB) that this\nvirtual machine can consume, regardless of available resources. The default\nis no limit.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of memory (in MB) that this\nvirtual machine is guaranteed. The default is no reservation.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The allocation level for memory resources.\nCan be one of <code>high</code>, <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>custom</code>. Default: <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_share_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of memory shares allocated to\nthe virtual machine when the <code>memory_share_level</code> is <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"advanced-options",description:'<h3 id="advanced-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#advanced-options" name="advanced-options">\xbb</a>\n  Advanced options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>The following options control advanced operation of the virtual machine, or\ncontrol various parts of Terraform workflow, and should not need to be modified\nduring basic operation of the resource. Only change these options if they are\nexplicitly required, or if you are having trouble with Terraform's default\nbehavior.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"enable_disk_uuid",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Expose the UUIDs of attached virtual disks to\nthe virtual machine, allowing access to them in the guest. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"hv_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The (non-nested) hardware virtualization setting for\nthis virtual machine. Can be one of <code>hvAuto</code>, <code>hvOn</code>, or <code>hvOff</code>. Default:\n<code>hvAuto</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ept_rvi_mode",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The EPT/RVI (hardware memory virtualization)\nsetting for this virtual machine. Can be one of <code>automatic</code>, <code>on</code>, or <code>off</code>.\nDefault: <code>automatic</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"nested_hv_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable nested hardware virtualization on\nthis virtual machine, facilitating nested virtualization in the guest.\nDefault: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"enable_logging",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable logging of virtual machine events to a\nlog file stored in the virtual machine directory. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_performance_counters_enabled",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Enable CPU performance\ncounters on this virtual machine. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"swap_placement_policy",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The swap file placement policy for this\nvirtual machine. Can be one of <code>inherit</code>, <code>hostLocal</code>, or <code>vmDirectory</code>.\nDefault: <code>inherit</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"latency_sensitivity",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls the scheduling delay of the\nvirtual machine. Use a higher sensitivity for applications that require lower\nlatency, such as VOIP, media player applications, or applications that\nrequire frequent access to mouse or keyboard devices. Can be one of <code>low</code>,\n<code>normal</code>, <code>medium</code>, or <code>high</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Do not use a <code>latency_sensitivity</code> setting of <code>low</code> or <code>medium</code> on\nhosts running ESXi 6.0 or older. Doing so may result in virtual machine startup\nissues or spurious diffs in Terraform. In addition, on higher sensitivities,\nyou may have to adjust <a href="#memory_reservation"><code>memory_reservation</code></a> to the full\namount of memory provisioned for the virtual machine.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"wait_for_guest_net_timeout",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of time, in minutes, to\nwait for an available IP address on this virtual machine\'s NICs. Older\nversions of VMware Tools do not populate this property. In those cases, this\nwaiter can be disabled and the\n<a href="#wait_for_guest_ip_timeout"><code>wait_for_guest_ip_timeout</code></a> waiter can be used\ninstead. A value less than 1 disables the waiter. Default: 5 minutes.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"wait_for_guest_net_routable",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Controls whether or not the guest\nnetwork waiter waits for a routable address. When <code>false</code>, the waiter does\nnot wait for a default gateway, nor are IP addresses checked against any\ndiscovered default gateways as part of its success criteria. This property is\nignored if the <a href="#wait_for_guest_ip_timeout"><code>wait_for_guest_ip_timeout</code></a>\nwaiter is used. Default: <code>true</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"wait_for_guest_ip_timeout",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of time, in minutes, to\nwait for an available guest IP address on this virtual machine. This should\nonly be used if your version of VMware Tools does not allow the\n<a href="#wait_for_guest_net_timeout"><code>wait_for_guest_net_timeout</code></a> waiter to be\nused. A value less than 1 disables the waiter. Default: 0.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ignored_guest_ips",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> List of IP addresses to ignore while waiting\nfor an available IP address using either of the waiters. Any IP addresses in\nthis list will be ignored if they show up so that the waiter will continue to\nwait for a real IP address. Default: [].\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"shutdown_wait_timeout",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of time, in minutes, to wait\nfor a graceful guest shutdown when making necessary updates to the virtual\nmachine. If <code>force_power_off</code> is set to true, the VM will be force powered-off\nafter this timeout, otherwise an error is returned. Default: 3 minutes.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"migrate_wait_timeout",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The amount of time, in minutes, to wait\nfor a virtual machine migration to complete before failing. Default: 10\nminutes. Also see the section on <a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual machine\nmigration</a>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"force_power_off",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> If a guest shutdown failed or timed out while\nupdating or destroying (see\n<a href="#shutdown_wait_timeout"><code>shutdown_wait_timeout</code></a>), force the power-off of\nthe virtual machine. Default: <code>true</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"scsi_controller_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of SCSI controllers that\nTerraform manages on this virtual machine. This directly affects the amount\nof disks you can add to the virtual machine and the maximum disk unit number.\nNote that lowering this value does not remove controllers. Default: <code>1</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>scsi_controller_count</code> should only be modified when you will need\nmore than 15 disks on a single virtual machine, or in rare cases that require a\ndedicated controller for certain disks. HashiCorp does not support exploiting\nthis value to add out-of-band devices.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"disk-options",description:'<h3 id="disk-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#disk-options" name="disk-options">\xbb</a>\n  Disk options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>Virtual disks are managed by adding an instance of the <code>disk</code> block.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>At the very least, there must be <code>name</code> and <code>size</code> attributes. <code>unit_number</code> is\nrequired for any disk other than the first, and there must be at least one\nresource with the implicit number of 0.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>An abridged multi-disk example is below:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">disk</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">label</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"disk0"</span>\n    <span class="n">size</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"10"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">disk</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">label</span>       <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"disk1"</span>\n    <span class="n">size</span>        <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"100"</span>\n    <span class="n">unit_number</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"label",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> A label for the disk. Forces a new disk if changed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> It\'s recommended that you set the disk label to a format matching\n<code>diskN</code>, where <code>N</code> is the number of the disk, starting from disk number 0. This\nwill ensure that your configuration is compatible when importing a virtual\nmachine. For more information, see the section on <a href="#importing">importing</a>.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Do not choose a label that starts with <code>orphaned_disk_</code> (example:\n<code>orphaned_disk_0</code>), as this prefix is reserved for disks that Terraform does\nnot recognize, such as disks that are attached externally. Terraform will issue\nan error if you try to label a disk with this prefix.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> An alias for both <code>label</code> and <code>path</code>, the latter when\nusing <code>attach</code>. Required if not using <code>label</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> This parameter has been deprecated and will be removed in future\nversions of the vSphere provider. You cannot use <code>name</code> on a disk that has\npreviously had a <code>label</code>, and using this argument is not recommend for new\nconfigurations.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> In previous versions of the vSphere provider this argument\ncontrolled file names for non-attached disks - this behavior has now been\nremoved, and the only time this controls path is when attaching a disk\nexternally with <code>attach</code> when the <code>path</code> field is not specified.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"size",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The size of the disk, in GB.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"unit_number",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The disk number on the SCSI bus. The maximum value\nfor this setting is the value of\n<a href="#scsi_controller_count"><code>scsi_controller_count</code></a> times 15, minus 1 (so <code>14</code>,\n<code>29</code>, <code>44</code>, and <code>59</code>, for 1-4 controllers respectively). The default is <code>0</code>,\nfor which one disk must be set to. Duplicate unit numbers are not allowed.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> A <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> to the datastore for this virtual disk. The default is\nto use the datastore of the virtual machine. See the section on <a href="#virtual-machine-migration">virtual\nmachine migration</a> for details on changing this\nvalue.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Datastores cannot be assigned to individual disks when\n<a href="#datastore_cluster_id"><code>datastore_cluster_id</code></a> is in use.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"attach",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Attach an external disk instead of creating a new one.\nImplies and conflicts with <code>keep_on_remove</code>. If set, you cannot set <code>size</code>,\n<code>eagerly_scrub</code>, or <code>thin_provisioned</code>. Must set <code>path</code> if used.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> External disks cannot be attached when\n<a href="#datastore_cluster_id"><code>datastore_cluster_id</code></a> is in use.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"path",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> When using <code>attach</code>, this parameter controls the path of\na virtual disk to attach externally. Otherwise, it is a computed attribute\nthat contains the virtual disk's current filename.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"keep_on_remove",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Keep this disk when removing the device or\ndestroying the virtual machine. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disk_mode",description:'<li><p><a name="disk_mode"></a><a href="#disk_mode"><code>disk_mode</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The mode of this this virtual disk for purposes of\nwrites and snapshotting. Can be one of <code>append</code>, <code>independent_nonpersistent</code>,\n<code>independent_persistent</code>, <code>nonpersistent</code>, <code>persistent</code>, or <code>undoable</code>.\nDefault: <code>persistent</code>. For an explanation of options, click\n<a href="https://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-6-5/topic/com.vmware.wssdk.apiref.doc/vim.vm.device.VirtualDiskOption.DiskMode.html">here</a>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"eagerly_scrub",description:'<li><p><a name="eagerly_scrub"></a><a href="#eagerly_scrub"><code>eagerly_scrub</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, the disk space is zeroed out\non VM creation. This will delay the creation of the disk or virtual machine.\nCannot be set to <code>true</code> when <code>thin_provisioned</code> is <code>true</code>.  See the section\non <a href="#picking-a-disk-type">picking a disk type</a>.  Default: <code>false</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"thin_provisioned",description:'<li><p><a name="thin_provisioned"></a><a href="#thin_provisioned"><code>thin_provisioned</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> If <code>true</code>, this disk is thin provisioned,\nwith space for the file being allocated on an as-needed basis. Cannot be set\nto <code>true</code> when <code>eagerly_scrub</code> is <code>true</code>. See the section on <a href="#picking-a-disk-type">picking a disk\ntype</a>. Default: <code>true</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disk_sharing",description:'<li><p><a name="disk_sharing"></a><a href="#disk_sharing"><code>disk_sharing</code></a> - <strong>(Optional)</strong> The sharing mode of this virtual disk. Can be one\nof <code>sharingMultiWriter</code> or <code>sharingNone</code>. Default: <code>sharingNone</code>.</p>\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Disk sharing is only available on vSphere 6.0 and higher.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"write_through",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If <code>true</code>, writes for this disk are sent\ndirectly to the filesystem immediately instead of being buffered. Default:\n<code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"io_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The upper limit of IOPS that this disk can use. The\ndefault is no limit.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"io_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The I/O reservation (guarantee) that this disk\nhas, in IOPS.  The default is no reservation.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"io_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The share allocation level for this disk. Can\nbe one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. Default: <code>normal</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"io_share_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The share count for this disk when the share\nlevel is <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"computed-disk-attributes",description:'<h4 id="computed-disk-attributes">\n<a class="anchor" href="#computed-disk-attributes" name="computed-disk-attributes">\xbb</a>\n  Computed disk attributes\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"uuid",description:"The UUID of the virtual disk's VMDK file. This is used to track the\nvirtual disk on the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"picking-a-disk-type",description:'<h4 id="picking-a-disk-type">\n<a class="anchor" href="#picking-a-disk-type" name="picking-a-disk-type">\xbb</a>\n  Picking a disk type\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The <code>eagerly_scrub</code> and <code>thin_provisioned</code> options control the space allocation\ntype of a virtual disk. These show up in the vSphere console as a unified\nenumeration of options, the equivalents of which are explained below. The\ndefaults in Terraform are the equivalent of thin provisioning.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"eagerly_scrub",description:"<li><strong>Thick provisioned lazy zeroed:</strong> Both <code>eagerly_scrub</code> and\n<code>thin_provisioned</code> should be set to <code>false</code>.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"eagerly_scrub",description:"<li><strong>Thick provisioned eager zeroed:</strong> <code>eagerly_scrub</code> should be set to true,\nand <code>thin_provisioned</code> should be set to <code>false</code>.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"eagerly_scrub",description:"<li><strong>Thin provisioned:</strong> <code>eagerly_scrub</code> should be set to <code>false</code>, and\n<code>thin_provisioned</code> should be set to <code>true</code>.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<p>For the technical details of each virtual disk provisioning policy, click\n<a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-4C0F4D73-82F2-4B81-8AA7-1DD752A8A5AC.html">here</a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Not all disk types are available on some types of datastores.\nAttempting to set options inappropriate for a datastore that a disk is deployed\nto will result in a successful initial apply, but vSphere will silently correct\nthe options, and subsequent plans will fail with an appropriate error message\nuntil the settings are corrected.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The disk type cannot be changed once set.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"network-interface-options",description:'<h3 id="network-interface-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#network-interface-options" name="network-interface-options">\xbb</a>\n  Network interface options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>Network interfaces are managed by adding an instance of the <code>network_interface</code>\nblock.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Interfaces are assigned to devices in the specific order they are declared.\nThis has different implications for different operating systems.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Given the following example:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.public.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.private.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The first interface with the <code>public</code> network assigned to it would show up in\norder before the interface assigned to <code>private</code>. On some Linux systems, this\nmight mean that the first interface would show up as <code>eth0</code> and the second\nwould show up as <code>eth1</code>.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"network_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object reference\nID</a> of the network to connect this interface to.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"adapter_type",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The network interface type. Can be one of\n<code>e1000</code>, <code>e1000e</code>, or <code>vmxnet3</code>. Default: <code>vmxnet3</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"use_static_mac",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If true, the <code>mac_address</code> field is treated as\na static MAC address and set accordingly. Setting this to <code>true</code> requires\n<code>mac_address</code> to be set. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"mac_address",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The MAC address of this network interface. Can\nonly be manually set if <code>use_static_mac</code> is true, otherwise this is a\ncomputed value that gives the current MAC address of this interface.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"bandwidth_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The upper bandwidth limit of this network\ninterface, in Mbits/sec. The default is no limit.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"bandwidth_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The bandwidth reservation of this\nnetwork interface, in Mbits/sec. The default is no reservation.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"bandwidth_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The bandwidth share allocation level for\nthis interface. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. Default:\n<code>normal</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"bandwidth_share_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The share count for this network\ninterface when the share level is <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cdrom-options",description:'<h3 id="cdrom-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#cdrom-options" name="cdrom-options">\xbb</a>\n  CDROM options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>A single virtual CDROM device can be created and attached to the virtual\nmachine. The resource supports attaching a CDROM from a datastore ISO or\nusing a remote client device.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>An example is below:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">cdrom</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">datastore_id</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_datastore.iso_datastore.id}"</span>\n    <span class="n">path</span>         <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"ISOs/os-livecd.iso"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"client_device",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Indicates whether the device should be backed by\nremote client device. Conflicts with <code>datastore_id</code> and <code>path</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_id",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The datastore ID that the ISO is located in.\nRequried for using a datastore ISO. Conflicts with <code>client_device</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"path",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The path to the ISO file. Required for using a datastore\nISO. Conflicts with <code>client_device</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Either <code>client_device</code> (for a remote backed CDROM) or <code>datastore_id</code>\nand path (for a datastore ISO backed CDROM) are required.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Some CDROM drive types are currently unsupported by this resource,\nsuch as pass-through devices. If these drives are present in a cloned template,\nor added outside of Terraform, they will have their configurations corrected to\nthat of the defined device, or removed if no <code>cdrom</code> block is present.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"virtual-device-computed-options",description:'<h3 id="virtual-device-computed-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#virtual-device-computed-options" name="virtual-device-computed-options">\xbb</a>\n  Virtual device computed options\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>Configured virtual devices (<code>disk</code>, <code>network_interface</code>, and <code>cdrom</code>) all\nexport the following attributes. These options help locate the device on future\nTerraform runs. The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"key",description:"The ID of the device within the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"device_address",description:"An address internal to Terraform that helps locate the\ndevice when <code>key</code> is unavailable. This follows a convention of\n<code>CONTROLLER_TYPE:BUS_NUMBER:UNIT_NUMBER</code>. Example: <code>scsi:0:1</code> means device\nunit 1 on SCSI bus 0.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"creating-a-virtual-machine-from-a-template",description:'<h2 id="creating-a-virtual-machine-from-a-template">\n<a class="anchor" href="#creating-a-virtual-machine-from-a-template" name="creating-a-virtual-machine-from-a-template">\xbb</a>\n  Creating a Virtual Machine from a Template\n</h2>',elementType:"h2"},{name:"",description:"<p>The <code>clone</code> block can be used to create a new virtual machine from an existing\nvirtual machine or template. The resource supports both making a complete copy\nof a virtual machine, or cloning from a snapshot (otherwise known as a linked\nclone).</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<p>See the <a href="#cloning-and-customization-example">cloning and customization\nexample</a> for a usage synopsis.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Changing any option in <code>clone</code> after creation forces a new\nresource.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> Cloning requires vCenter and is not supported on direct ESXi\nconnections.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options available in the <code>clone</code> block are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"template_uuid",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The UUID of the source virtual machine or\ntemplate.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"linked_clone",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Clone this virtual machine from a snapshot.\nTemplates must have a single snapshot only in order to be eligible. Default:\n<code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"timeout",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The timeout, in minutes, to wait for the virtual\nmachine clone to complete. Default: 30 minutes.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"customize",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The customization spec for this clone. This allows\nthe user to configure the virtual machine post-clone. For more details, see\n<a href="#virtual-machine-customization">virtual machine customization</a>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"virtual-machine-customization",description:'<h3 id="virtual-machine-customization">\n<a class="anchor" href="#virtual-machine-customization" name="virtual-machine-customization">\xbb</a>\n  Virtual machine customization\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>As part of the <code>clone</code> operation, a virtual machine can be\n<a href="https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/6.5/com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-58E346FF-83AE-42B8-BE58-253641D257BC.html">customized</a> to configure host, network, or licensing\nsettings.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<p>To perform virtual machine customization as a part of the clone process,\nspecify the <code>customize</code> block with the respective customization options, nested\nwithin the <code>clone</code> block. Windows guests are customized using Sysprep, which\nwill result in the machine SID being reset. Before using customization, check\nis that your source VM meets the <a href="https://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-50/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc_50%2FGUID-80F3F5B5-F795-45F1-B0FA-3709978113D5.html">requirements</a>\nfor guest OS customization on vSphere. See the <a href="#cloning-and-customization-example">cloning and customization\nexample</a> for a usage synopsis.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The settings for <code>customize</code> are as follows:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"customization-timeout-settings",description:'<h4 id="customization-timeout-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#customization-timeout-settings" name="customization-timeout-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Customization timeout settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"timeout",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The time, in minutes that Terraform waits for\ncustomization to complete before failing. The default is 10 minutes, and\nsetting the value to 0 or a negative value disables the waiter altogether.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"network-interface-settings",description:'<h4 id="network-interface-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#network-interface-settings" name="network-interface-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Network interface settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>These settings, which should be specified in nested <code>network_interface</code> blocks\nwithin <a href="#virtual-machine-customization"><code>customize</code></a>, configure network\ninterfaces on a per-interface basis and are matched up to\n<a href="#network-interface-options"><code>network_interface</code></a> devices in the order they are\ndeclared.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Given the following example:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.public.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.private.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="o">...</span>\n\n    <span class="n">customize</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="o">...</span>\n\n      <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n        <span class="n">ipv4_address</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"10.0.0.10"</span>\n        <span class="n">ipv4_netmask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">24</span>\n      <span class="p">}</span>\n\n      <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n        <span class="n">ipv4_address</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"172.16.0.10"</span>\n        <span class="n">ipv4_netmask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">24</span>\n      <span class="p">}</span>\n\n      <span class="n">ipv4_gateway</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"10.0.0.1"</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The first set of <code>network_interface</code> data would be assigned to the <code>public</code>\ninterface, and the second to the <code>private</code> interface.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>To use DHCP, declare an empty <code>network_interface</code> block for each interface\nbeing configured. So the above example would look like:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.public.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">network_id</span>   <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_network.private.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="o">...</span>\n\n    <span class="n">customize</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="o">...</span>\n\n      <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{}</span>\n\n      <span class="n">network_interface</span> <span class="p">{}</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"dns_server_list",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Network interface-specific DNS server settings\nfor Windows operating systems. Ignored on Linux and possibly other operating\nsystems",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dns_domain",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Network interface-specific DNS search domain for\nWindows operating systems. Ignored on Linux and possibly other operating\nsystems",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv4_address",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IPv4 address assigned to this network adapter. If left\nblank or not included, DHCP is used.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv4_netmask",description:" The IPv4 subnet mask, in bits (example: <code>24</code> for\n255.255.255.0).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv6_address",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IPv6 address assigned to this network adapter. If left\nblank or not included, auto-configuration is used.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv6_netmask",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IPv6 subnet mask, in bits (example: <code>32</code>).\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The minimum setting for IPv4 in a customization specification is\nDHCP. If you are setting up an IPv6-exclusive network without DHCP, you might\nneed to set <a href="#wait_for_guest_net_timeout"><code>wait_for_guest_net_timeout</code></a> to a\nhigh enough value to cover the DHCP timeout of your virtual machine, or turn it\noff altogether by supplying a zero or negative value. Keep in mind that turning\noff <code>wait_for_guest_net_timeout</code> will more than likely mean that IP addresses\nwill not be reported to any provisioners you may have configured on the\nresource.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"global-routing-settings",description:'<h4 id="global-routing-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#global-routing-settings" name="global-routing-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Global routing settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>VM customization under the <code>vsphere_virtual_machine</code> resource does not take a\nper-interface gateway setting, but rather default routes are configured on a\nglobal basis. For an example, see the <a href="#network-interface-settings">network interface settings\nsection</a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The settings here must match the IP/mask of at least one <code>network_interface</code>\nsupplied to customization.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"ipv4_gateway",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IPv4 default gateway when using\n<code>network_interface</code> customization on the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"ipv6_gateway",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IPv6 default gateway when using\n<code>network_interface</code> customization on the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"global-dns-settings",description:'<h4 id="global-dns-settings">\n<a class="anchor" href="#global-dns-settings" name="global-dns-settings">\xbb</a>\n  Global DNS settings\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>The following settings configure DNS globally, generally for Linux systems. For\nWindows systems, this is done per-interface, see <a href="#network-interface-settings">network interface\nsettings</a>.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"dns_server_list",description:"The list of DNS servers to configure on a virtual\nmachine. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"dns_suffix_list",description:"A list of DNS search domains to add to the DNS\nconfiguration on the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"linux-customization-options",description:'<h4 id="linux-customization-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#linux-customization-options" name="linux-customization-options">\xbb</a>\n  Linux customization options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The settings in the <code>linux_options</code> block pertain to Linux guest OS\ncustomization. If you are customizing a Linux operating system, this section\nmust be included.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Example:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="o">...</span>\n\n    <span class="n">customize</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="o">...</span>\n\n      <span class="n">linux_options</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n        <span class="n">host_name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"terraform-test"</span>\n        <span class="n">domain</span>    <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"test.internal"</span>\n      <span class="p">}</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"host_name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The host name for this machine. This, along with\n<code>domain</code>, make up the FQDN of this virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"domain",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The domain name for this machine. This, along with\n<code>host_name</code>, make up the FQDN of this virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"hw_clock_utc",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Tells the operating system that the hardware\nclock is set to UTC. Default: <code>true</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"time_zone",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> Sets the time zone. For a list of possible\ncombinations, click <a href="https://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-6-5/topic/com.vmware.wssdk.apiref.doc/timezone.html">here</a>. The default is UTC.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"windows-customization-options",description:'<h4 id="windows-customization-options">\n<a class="anchor" href="#windows-customization-options" name="windows-customization-options">\xbb</a>\n  Windows customization options\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>The settings in the <code>windows_options</code> block pertain to Windows guest OS\ncustomization. If you are customizing a Windows operating system, this section\nmust be included.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>Example:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="o">...</span>\n\n    <span class="n">customize</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="o">...</span>\n\n      <span class="n">windows_options</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n        <span class="n">computer_name</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"terraform-test"</span>\n        <span class="n">workgroup</span>      <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"test"</span>\n        <span class="n">admin_password</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"VMw4re"</span>\n      <span class="p">}</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The options are:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"computer_name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The computer name of this virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"admin_password",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The administrator password for this virtual\nmachine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>admin_password</code> is a sensitive field in Terraform and will not be\noutput on-screen, but is stored in state and sent to the VM in plain text -\nkeep this in mind when provisioning your infrastructure.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"workgroup",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The workgroup name for this virtual machine. One of\nthis or <code>join_domain</code> must be included.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"join_domain",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The domain to join for this virtual machine. One\nof this or <code>workgroup</code> must be included.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"domain_admin_user",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The user of the domain administrator used to\njoin this virtual machine to the domain. Required if you are setting <code>join_domain</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"domain_admin_password",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The password of the domain administrator\nused to join this virtual machine to the domain. Required if you are setting\n<code>join_domain</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>domain_admin_password</code> is a sensitive field in Terraform and will\nnot be output on-screen, but is stored in state and sent to the VM in plain\ntext - keep this in mind when provisioning your infrastructure.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"full_name",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The full name of the user of this virtual machine.\nThis populates the "user" field in the general Windows system information.\nDefault: <code>Administrator</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"organization_name",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The organization name this virtual machine\nis being installed for.  This populates the "organization" field in the\ngeneral Windows system information.  Default: <code>Managed by Terraform</code>.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"product_key",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The product key for this virtual machine. The\ndefault is no key.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"run_once_command_list",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> A list of commands to run at first user\nlogon, after guest customization. Each command is limited by the API to 260\ncharacters.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"auto_logon",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Specifies whether or not the VM automatically logs\non as Administrator. Default: <code>false</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"auto_logon_count",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Specifies how many times the VM should auto-logon\nthe Administrator account when <code>auto_logon</code> is true. This should be set\naccordingly to ensure that all of your commands that run in\n<code>run_once_command_list</code> can log in to run. Default: <code>1</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"time_zone",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The new time zone for the virtual machine. This is a\nnumeric, sysprep-dictated, timezone code. For a list of codes, click\n<a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms912391(v=winembedded.11).aspx">here</a>. The default is <code>85</code> (GMT/UTC).\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"supplying-your-own-sysprep-file",description:'<h4 id="supplying-your-own-sysprep-file">\n<a class="anchor" href="#supplying-your-own-sysprep-file" name="supplying-your-own-sysprep-file">\xbb</a>\n  Supplying your own SysPrep file\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:"<p>Alternative to the <code>windows_options</code> supplied above, you can instead supply\nyour own <code>sysprep.inf</code> file contents via the <code>windows_sysprep_text</code> option.\nThis allows full control of the customization process out-of-band of vSphere.\nExample below:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="o">...</span>\n\n    <span class="n">customize</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="o">...</span>\n\n      <span class="n">windows_sysprep_text</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${file("</span><span class="err">$</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="n">path</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="nf">module</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">sysprep</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="nf">inf</span><span class="s2">")}"</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>Note this option is mutually exclusive to <code>windows_options</code> - one must not be\nincluded if the other is specified.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration",description:'<h3 id="using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration">\n<a class="anchor" href="#using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration" name="using-vapp-properties-to-supply-ovf-ova-configuration">\xbb</a>\n  Using vApp properties to supply OVF/OVA configuration\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:'<p>Alternative to the settings in <code>customize</code>, one can use the settings in the\n<code>properties</code> section of the <code>vapp</code> block to supply configuration parameters to\na virtual machine cloned from a template that came from an imported OVF or OVA\nfile. Both GuestInfo and ISO transport methods are supported. For templates\nthat use ISO transport, a CDROM backed by client device is required. See <a href="#cdrom-options">CDROM\noptions</a> for details.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> The only supported usage path for vApp properties is for existing\nuser-configurable keys. These generally come from an existing template that was\ncreated from an imported OVF or OVA file. You cannot set values for vApp\nproperties on virtual machines created from scratch, virtual machines lacking a\nvApp configuration, or on property keys that do not exist.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"",description:"<p>The configuration looks similar to the one below:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="nb">clone</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">template_uuid</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_virtual_machine.template_from_ovf.id}"</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">vapp</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">properties</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n      <span class="s2">"guestinfo.tf.internal.id"</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"42"</span>\n    <span class="p">}</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"additional-requirements-and-notes-for-cloning",description:'<h3 id="additional-requirements-and-notes-for-cloning">\n<a class="anchor" href="#additional-requirements-and-notes-for-cloning" name="additional-requirements-and-notes-for-cloning">\xbb</a>\n  Additional requirements and notes for cloning\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>Note that when cloning from a template, there are additional requirements in\nboth the resource configuration and source template:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"The virtual machine must not be powered on at the time of cloning.\n",description:"<li>The virtual machine must not be powered on at the time of cloning.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"All disks on the virtual machine must be SCSI disks.\n",description:"<li>All disks on the virtual machine must be SCSI disks.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disk",description:"<li>You must specify at least the same number of <code>disk</code> devices as there are\ndisks that exist in the template. These devices are ordered and lined up by\nthe <code>unit_number</code> attribute. Additional disks can be added past this.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"size",description:"<li>The <code>size</code> of a virtual disk must be at least the same size as its\ncounterpart disk in the template.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"linked_clone",description:"<li>When using <code>linked_clone</code>, the <code>size</code>, <code>thin_provisioned</code>, and\n<code>eagerly_scrub</code> settings for each disk must be an exact match to the\nindividual disk's counterpart in the source template.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"scsi_controller_count",description:'<li>The <a href="#scsi_controller_count"><code>scsi_controller_count</code></a> setting should be\nconfigured as necessary to cover all of the disks on the template. For best\nresults, only configure this setting for the amount of controllers you will\nneed to cover your disk quantity and bandwidth needs, and configure your\ntemplate accordingly. For most workloads, this setting should be kept at its\ndefault of <code>1</code>, and all disks in the template should reside on the single,\nprimary controller.\n</li>',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"scsi_type",description:"<li>Some operating systems (such as Windows) do not respond well to a change in\ndisk controller type, so when using such OSes, take care to ensure that\n<code>scsi_type</code> is set to an exact match of the template's controller set. For\nmaximum compatibility, make sure the SCSI controllers on the source template\nare all the same type.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:'<p>To ease the gathering of some of these options, you can use the\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/d/virtual_machine.html"><code>vsphere_virtual_machine</code> data source</a>, which\nwill give you disk attributes, network interface types, SCSI bus types, and\nalso the guest ID of the source template.  See the <a href="#cloning-and-customization-example">cloning and customization\nexample</a> for usage details.</p>',elementType:"p"},{name:"virtual-machine-migration",description:'<h2 id="virtual-machine-migration">\n<a class="anchor" href="#virtual-machine-migration" name="virtual-machine-migration">\xbb</a>\n  Virtual Machine Migration\n</h2>',elementType:"h2"},{name:"",description:"<p>The <code>vsphere_virtual_machine</code> resource supports live migration (otherwise known\nas vMotion) both on the host and storage level. One can migrate the entire VM\nto another host, cluster, resource pool, or datastore, and migrate or pin a\nsingle disk to a specific datastore.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"host-cluster-and-resource-pool-migration",description:'<h3 id="host-cluster-and-resource-pool-migration">\n<a class="anchor" href="#host-cluster-and-resource-pool-migration" name="host-cluster-and-resource-pool-migration">\xbb</a>\n  Host, cluster, and resource pool migration\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>To migrate the virtual machine to another host or resource pool, change the\n<code>host_system_id</code> or <code>resource_pool_id</code> to the manged object IDs of the new host\nor resource pool accordingly. To change the virtual machine's cluster or\nstandalone host, select a resource pool within the specific target.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:"<p>The same rules apply for migration as they do for VM creation - any host\nspecified needs to be a part of the resource pool supplied. Also keep in mind\nthe implications of moving the virtual machine to a resource pool in another\ncluster or standalone host, namely ensuring that all hosts in the cluster (or\nthe single standalone host) have access to the datastore that the virtual\nmachine is in.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"storage-migration",description:'<h3 id="storage-migration">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-migration" name="storage-migration">\xbb</a>\n  Storage migration\n</h3>',elementType:"h3"},{name:"",description:"<p>Storage migration can be done on two levels:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"datastore_id",description:"<li>Global datastore migration can be handled by changing the global\n<code>datastore_id</code> attribute. This triggers a storage migration for all disks\nthat do not have an explicit <code>datastore_id</code> specified.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"datastore_cluster_id",description:"<li>When using Storage DRS through the <code>datastore_cluster_id</code> attribute, the\nentire virtual machine can be migrated from one datastore cluster to another\nby changing the value of this setting. In addition, when\n<code>datastore_cluster_id</code> is in use, any disks that drift to datastores outside\nof the datastore cluster via such actions as manual modification will be\nmigrated back to the datastore cluster on the next apply.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"disk",description:"<li>An individual <code>disk</code> device can be migrated by manually specifying the\n<code>datastore_id</code> in its configuration block. This also pins it to the specific\ndatastore that is specified - if at a later time the VM and any unpinned\ndisks migrate to another host, the disk will stay on the specified datastore.\n</li>",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"",description:"<p>An example of datastore pinning is below. As long as the datastore in the\n<code>pinned_datastore</code> data source does not change, any change to the standard\n<code>vm_datastore</code> data source will not affect the data disk - the disk will stay\nwhere it is.</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight hcl"><code><span class="n">resource</span> <span class="s2">"vsphere_virtual_machine"</span> <span class="s2">"vm"</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n\n  <span class="n">datastore_id</span>     <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_datastore.vm_datastore.id}"</span>\n\n  <span class="n">disk</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">label</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"disk0"</span>\n    <span class="n">size</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">10</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="n">disk</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n    <span class="n">datastore_id</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"${data.vsphere_datastore.pinned_datastore.id}"</span>\n    <span class="n">label</span>        <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"disk1"</span>\n    <span class="n">size</span>         <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">100</span>\n    <span class="n">unit_number</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>\n  <span class="p">}</span>\n\n  <span class="o">...</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"storage-migration-restrictions",description:'<h4 id="storage-migration-restrictions">\n<a class="anchor" href="#storage-migration-restrictions" name="storage-migration-restrictions">\xbb</a>\n  Storage migration restrictions\n</h4>',elementType:"h4"},{name:"",description:'<p>Note that you cannot migrate external disks added with the <code>attach</code> parameter.\nAs these disks have usually been created and assigned to a datastore outside of\nthe scope of the <code>vsphere_virtual_machine</code> resource in question, such as by\nusing the <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/virtual_disk.html"><code>vsphere_virtual_disk</code> resource</a>,\nmanagement of such disks would render their configuration unstable.</p>',elementType:"p"}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/virtual_machine.html",docType:""},{id:30,type:"  vsphere_virtual_machine_snapshot",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"",description:'<div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> All attributes in the <code>vsphere_virtual_machine_snapshot</code> resource\nare immutable and force a new resource if changed.</p>\n</div>',elementType:"div"},{name:"virtual_machine_uuid",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The virtual machine UUID.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"snapshot_name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the snapshot.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"description",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> A description for the snapshot.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, a dump of the internal state of the\nvirtual machine is included in the snapshot.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"quiesce",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, and the virtual machine is powered\non when the snapshot is taken, VMware Tools is used to quiesce the file\nsystem in the virtual machine.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"remove_children",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, the entire snapshot subtree\nis removed when this resource is destroyed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"consolidate",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> If set to <code>true</code>, the delta disks involved in this\nsnapshot will be consolidated into the parent when this resource is\ndestroyed.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/virtual_machine_snapshot.html",docType:""},{id:31,type:"  vsphere_vapp_container",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"name",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> The name of the vApp container.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"parent_resource_pool_id",description:'<strong>(Required)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a>\nof the parent resource pool. This can be the root resource pool for a cluster\nor standalone host, or a resource pool itself. When moving a vApp container\nfrom one parent resource pool to another, both must share a common root\nresource pool or the move will fail.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"parent_folder_id",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The <a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/index.html#use-of-managed-object-references-by-the-vsphere-provider">managed object ID</a> of\nthe vApp container\'s parent folder.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU allocation level. The level is a\nsimplified view of shares. Levels map to a pre-determined set of numeric\nvalues for shares. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. When\n<code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>high</code> are specified values in <code>cpu_shares</code> will be\nignored.  Default: <code>normal</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_shares",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of shares allocated for CPU. Used to\ndetermine resource allocation in case of resource contention. If this is set,\n<code>cpu_share_level</code> must be <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Amount of CPU (MHz) that is guaranteed\navailable to the vApp container. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_expandable",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines if the reservation on a vApp\ncontainer can grow beyond the specified value if the parent resource pool has\nunreserved resources. Default: <code>true</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"cpu_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU utilization of a vApp container will not\nexceed this limit, even if there are available resources. Set to <code>-1</code> for\nunlimited.\nDefault: <code>-1</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_share_level",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU allocation level. The level is a\nsimplified view of shares. Levels map to a pre-determined set of numeric\nvalues for shares. Can be one of <code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, <code>high</code>, or <code>custom</code>. When\n<code>low</code>, <code>normal</code>, or <code>high</code> are specified values in <code>memory_shares</code> will be\nignored.  Default: <code>normal</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_shares",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The number of shares allocated for CPU. Used to\ndetermine resource allocation in case of resource contention. If this is set,\n<code>memory_share_level</code> must be <code>custom</code>.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_reservation",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Amount of CPU (MHz) that is guaranteed\navailable to the vApp container. Default: <code>0</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_expandable",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines if the reservation on a vApp\ncontainer can grow beyond the specified value if the parent resource pool has\nunreserved resources. Default: <code>true</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"memory_limit",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> The CPU utilization of a vApp container will not\nexceed this limit, even if there are available resources. Set to <code>-1</code> for\nunlimited.\nDefault: <code>-1</code>\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"tags",description:'<strong>(Optional)</strong> The IDs of any tags to attach to this resource. See\n<a href="/docs/providers/vsphere/r/tag.html#using-tags-in-a-supported-resource">here</a> for a reference on how to apply tags.\n',elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/vapp_container.html",docType:""},{id:32,type:"  vsphere_vapp_entity",properties:[{name:"",description:"<p>The following arguments are supported:</p>",elementType:"p"},{name:"target_id",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> [Managed object ID|docs-about-morefs] of the entity\nto power on or power off. This can be a virtual machine or a vApp. \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"container_id",description:"<strong>(Required)</strong> [Managed object ID|docs-about-morefs] of the vApp\ncontainer the entity is a member of.\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"start_order",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Order to start and stop target in vApp. Default: 1\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"start_action",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> How to start the entity. Valid settings are none\nor powerOn. If set to none, then the entity does not participate in auto-start.\nDefault: powerOn\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"start_delay",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Delay in seconds before continuing with the next\nentity in the order of entities to be started. Default: 120 \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"stop_action",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Defines the stop action for the entity. Can be set\nto none, powerOff, guestShutdown, or suspend. If set to none, then the entity\ndoes not participate in auto-stop. Default: powerOff \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"stop_delay",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Delay in seconds before continuing with the next\nentity in the order sequence. This is only used if the stopAction is\nguestShutdown. Default: 120 \n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1},{name:"wait_for_guest",description:"<strong>(Optional)</strong> Determines if the VM should be marked as being\nstarted when VMware Tools are ready instead of waiting for <code>start_delay</code>. This\nproperty has no effect for vApps. Default: false\n",elementType:"li",listDepth:1}],docsUrl:"https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/vsphere/r/vapp_entity.html",docType:""}]}}]);